Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington, D.C.

00:00:16.790 --> 00:00:20.740
&gt;&gt; Levon Avdoyan: I have the
pleasure of introducing someone

00:00:20.740 --> 00:00:24.860
who did research in the African
and Middle Eastern Division.

00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:28.260
I also have the pleasure
to introduce someone who,

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:31.140
if we were giving an award
for innovative titles,

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:34.980
would no doubt have
won it today.

00:00:34.980 --> 00:00:38.970
To a Professor -- Assistant
Professor of History

00:00:38.970 --> 00:00:46.440
at Skidmore is going to speak
to us about "Biceps and Balls,

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:49.280
Physical Culture in
Late Ottoman Bolis."

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:52.010
And for those who -- of you
who don't know what Bolis is,

00:00:52.010 --> 00:00:56.220
Bolis -- Polis is the
Armenian word for Istanbul,

00:00:56.220 --> 00:01:00.050
Constantinople, and it
brings me great pleasure

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:03.210
to introduce Murat Yildiz.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:05.010
&gt;&gt; Yay.

00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:11.790
[ Applause ]

00:01:11.790 --> 00:01:14.280
&gt;&gt; Murat Yildiz: Levon,
you're too -- too kind.

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:18.280
So before I begin, I would like
to thank Levon and the Library

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:22.380
of Congress for organizing
this amazing conference

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:24.990
that really -- I think, we
can all attest to this --

00:01:24.990 --> 00:01:26.800
that reveals the
breadth and richness

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:29.720
of Armenian history and culture.

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:32.380
It's an honor to be here.

00:01:32.380 --> 00:01:37.030
My talk today, as Levon
mentioned, is entitled "Biceps

00:01:37.030 --> 00:01:41.630
and Balls, Physical Culture
in Late Ottoman Bolis."

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:45.860
Okay, so in fall 2010, I
started to conduct research

00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:47.940
for my dissertation
project in Istanbul.

00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:51.810
I initially envisioned the
dissertation as a study

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:55.240
of the intersection of sports,
nation building, the body,

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:56.880
and gender during
the late empire

00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:58.750
and early Turkish republic.

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:00.990
And more specifically,
what I wanted to do was,

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:04.200
I wanted to investigate the
ways in which the bodies

00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:08.580
of young men served as a
central site of nation-building.

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:11.760
Like many Ottoman historians, I
started in the [foreign word],

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:16.850
or the Ottoman archive for
the Prime Minister's office,

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:18.850
which basically --
which serves as the --

00:02:18.850 --> 00:02:22.710
as the primary repository
for state archival documents

00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:25.540
in Turkey related to
the Ottoman Empire.

00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:28.120
So my searches resulted
in me sifting

00:02:28.120 --> 00:02:31.900
through government reports
on physical education,

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:35.820
and team sports in schools,
government programs,

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:38.170
and voluntary associations.

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:40.340
They offered a number
of insights

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:42.560
into the burgeoning interest

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:45.390
in sports throughout
Istanbul during the time.

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:48.040
However, they left
me dissatisfied.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:50.760
They left me dissatisfied
for the following reason.

00:02:50.760 --> 00:02:52.480
The documents created
the impression

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:58.240
that the Ottoman government was
the central actor in spreading,

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:01.680
institutionalizing, and
popularizing sports.

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:03.810
And in order to complicate
this narrative,

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:05.770
I sought to diversify
my sources,

00:03:05.770 --> 00:03:09.130
and explore the representation
of sporting activities

00:03:09.130 --> 00:03:12.310
and institutions in the
expanding public sphere.

00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:15.880
And in order to do this,
I turned to the press.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.540
Magazines and newspapers
written in Ottoman Turkish

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:21.070
from the period offered
a rich set of textual

00:03:21.070 --> 00:03:23.930
and visual coverage,
and discursive framing

00:03:23.930 --> 00:03:27.890
of team sports -- mainly
soccer, gymnastics,

00:03:27.890 --> 00:03:30.110
competitions, and sports clubs.

00:03:30.110 --> 00:03:33.650
The Ottoman government wasn't
absent in these conversations.

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:37.020
However, it was de-centered
from the narrative.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:39.920
In other words, the Ottoman
government emerged as one

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:43.760
of many actors, albeit an
incredibly powerful one,

00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:47.600
contributing to the spread
and popularization of sports

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:49.450
in the center of the empire.

00:03:49.450 --> 00:03:53.330
And I found myself asking
what was the significance

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:56.610
of these different
representations of sports.

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:58.470
In order to answer
this question,

00:03:58.470 --> 00:04:02.220
I decided to bring these sources
and archives into dialogue.

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:05.650
And I did so by reading
magazines in the morning,

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:09.580
and files from the Ottoman
state archives in the evening.

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:13.050
Now, this methodological
exercise revealed a number

00:04:13.050 --> 00:04:15.410
of insights, one of which was

00:04:15.410 --> 00:04:19.570
that some non-government
institutions were represented

00:04:19.570 --> 00:04:22.580
in certain places
and not in others.

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:25.730
Specifically, I noticed
some clubs that emerged

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:29.570
in government reports
were absent --

00:04:29.570 --> 00:04:32.470
were absent from
discussions in the press.

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:35.630
Now, for example, this report --

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:40.290
this report from the
Interior Ministry is a list

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:43.570
of voluntary associations,
written in Ottoman Turkish,

00:04:43.570 --> 00:04:48.520
which included, but was not
restricted to sports clubs.

00:04:48.520 --> 00:04:50.950
Now, I was familiar
with some of these clubs

00:04:50.950 --> 00:04:54.160
from the sports press,
and others less so.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:57.910
I was familiar with
some -- others less so.

00:04:57.910 --> 00:05:01.670
So one of the clubs, which I
hadn't come across in the press,

00:05:01.670 --> 00:05:05.760
was the -- and this is
the Ottoman spelling,

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:08.440
Artivasat Gymnastique
Gymnyeti [phonetic].

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:10.540
And I'll say something about
the spelling in a second.

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:12.220
This was the spelling
in Ottoman Turkish.

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:15.030
This is around -- a
couple from -- a couple --

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:18.710
maybe one, two, three,
four, five from the bottom.

00:05:18.710 --> 00:05:22.450
Like all experienced researchers
-- and this is a joke --

00:05:22.450 --> 00:05:25.410
I turned to the all-knowing
web for answers.

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:32.360
I appreciate that [laughter].

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:35.890
Did not figure into
my table of contents.

00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:38.970
So these searches led me to
the work of Hayk Demoyan,

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:41.280
who was at that -- then,
and now, the director

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:43.170
of the Armenian Genocide
Museum in Yerevan.

00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:46.630
Now, at the time, Demoyan had
recently organized an exhibition

00:05:46.630 --> 00:05:48.870
at the museum, and
published a book

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:50.680
on Armenian sports
in the empire.

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:52.740
Now, these project reveal --

00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:55.270
these projects reveal to me

00:05:55.270 --> 00:06:00.280
that Artivast Gymanstique
Gymyeti [phonetic] had another

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:02.460
name, more than likely a more
commonly-used one during the

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:06.290
time, and that was Cruchesmeh
Marnamasagan Artivast

00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:07.590
Ugumph [phonetic].

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:10.740
Now, why hadn't I encountered
this club in other places,

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:12.810
is the question that I ask?

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:15.140
Were there other clubs,
and more specifically,

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:18.020
were there other Armenian
clubs and figures excluded

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:20.580
from the documents that
I had been reading?

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:23.390
And if so, what was
the significance

00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:26.740
of this seemingly-separate
sporting world

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:28.950
in late Ottoman Istanbul?

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:31.860
Now, I asked myself whether
early 20th Century sports

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:36.140
enthusiasts writing in Ottoman
Turkish knowingly excluded

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:37.590
Armenians from their
discussions.

00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:40.930
In other words, were they
unaware of Artivasts [phonetic]

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:43.380
and other Armenian
sports clubs' activities,

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:46.770
or were they knowingly
ignoring them?

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:50.230
Now, an image of
three sportsmen seemed

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:53.300
to indirectly provide
the answer.

00:06:53.300 --> 00:07:00.150
Now, this titillating image
featured three men posing

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:02.170
and flexing their
divine -- defined bodies.

00:07:02.170 --> 00:07:07.120
That was a slip, but
it was actually very

00:07:07.120 --> 00:07:08.470
enlightening [laughter].

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:10.910
Until that point, what had
captivated my attention

00:07:10.910 --> 00:07:13.970
about this and similar
images was the presentation

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:18.220
of a gendered athlete
that was modern, strong,

00:07:18.220 --> 00:07:20.490
beautiful, and also exotic.

00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:24.180
The text, however, now offered
a whole new layer of meaning.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:28.200
Now, at the top of the page,
the top right part of the page,

00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:32.010
the text reads "our robust
bodies, [foreign word]."

00:07:32.010 --> 00:07:35.320
Now, the three men
are [foreign word],

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:37.100
or the naval officer
[foreign word],

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:47.200
or the gymnastic instructor
of Galatasaray club,

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:49.930
and who was a major, [foreign
word], and the [foreign word].

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:58.430
Now, together, the text and
the images conveyed a number

00:07:58.430 --> 00:07:59.860
of points to readers.

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:05.140
First, these were
robust, beautiful bodies.

00:08:05.140 --> 00:08:10.580
Second, these Turkish male
bodies were cultivated

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:11.880
in sports clubs.

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:13.180
They're connected to --

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:15.790
these figures are
connected to institutions.

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:20.170
And third, these bodies
belonged to a group

00:08:20.170 --> 00:08:23.550
of people, not just themselves.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:29.160
Okay? So I asked, who were
claiming these bodies?

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:31.100
Was it the magazine?

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:36.310
Was it its readers, a broader
collective, a fan club?

00:08:36.310 --> 00:08:39.430
Was there a difference between
these different communities --

00:08:39.430 --> 00:08:42.490
communities of readers,
the magazine,

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:43.790
or a broader collective?

00:08:43.790 --> 00:08:47.540
Now, I concluded that the
Ottoman Turkish sports magazine,

00:08:47.540 --> 00:08:49.920
through this image and others,

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:54.170
was projecting an exclusive
reading of sports in Istanbul,

00:08:54.170 --> 00:08:57.530
one in which Ottoman
Turks were the main,

00:08:57.530 --> 00:08:59.570
if not the sole actors, okay?

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:03.050
And in doing so, what
the magazine was doing --

00:09:03.050 --> 00:09:07.490
it was erasing the presence
of some Armenians --

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:10.990
excuse me, some Ottomans, and
foregrounding the presence

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:13.510
of others in the world
of sports in the city.

00:09:13.510 --> 00:09:18.760
Now, this conclusion haunted
me, because of its implications.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:21.780
Like the magazine, at that
time, I was contributing

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:25.100
to the historical erasure
of many Ottoman citizens --

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:29.730
more broadly, and more
specifically, Armenians.

00:09:33.910 --> 00:09:36.710
Now, I asked, could I write
an alternative history

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:40.790
that accounted for, but did
not reproduce, this erasure?

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:44.300
And if so, what would
this history look like?

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:46.190
Was it different than the
project that I had set

00:09:46.190 --> 00:09:49.440
out to study as a
graduate student?

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:52.500
So I concluded that
the answers were yes,

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:54.400
I could write an
alternative history.

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:57.950
However, in order to do so, I
needed to expand my analysis

00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:00.920
of the historical actors,
spaces, and institutions

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:02.700
that made up physical
culture in late 19th

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:06.390
and early 20th Century
Constantinople.

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:07.690
What did this require?

00:10:07.690 --> 00:10:12.390
This required an expansion of
the project's archives, sources,

00:10:12.390 --> 00:10:15.040
as well as the languages
that I used.

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:19.010
And it was at this point that I
began to study western Armenian

00:10:19.010 --> 00:10:22.400
with a tutor, a very kind,
generous, and lovely tutor,

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:27.300
and consult Ottoman Turkish,
but also Armenian sources.

00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:29.890
Now, this proved to be
an immensely challenging,

00:10:29.890 --> 00:10:32.230
but also rewarding exercise.

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:35.710
Now, the new methodological
approach offered exciting

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:38.930
insights into the ways in
which Ottomans, from a plethora

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:41.140
of different ethno-religious
communities,

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:43.150
shaped the defining
contours of sports

00:10:43.150 --> 00:10:46.460
as a shared civic
culture in Istanbul.

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:50.180
As a result, this approach
fundamentally reconfigured the

00:10:50.180 --> 00:10:51.790
scope of the dissertation.

00:10:51.790 --> 00:10:55.860
And now, the metamorphosis of
the project enabled me to build

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:58.840
on the insights of a
new body of scholarship

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:03.600
that graduate students and
junior scholars of Armenian

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:05.540
and Ottoman studies
were producing

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:08.090
over the past decade, okay?

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:11.270
Now, bringing together sources
written in a diverse array

00:11:11.270 --> 00:11:15.500
of languages, investigating
spaces, and transformations

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:19.010
across ethno-religious
divisions, and refusing

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:24.050
to treat communal boundaries
separating Armenians as Turks

00:11:24.050 --> 00:11:27.820
as historically static
and impenetrable.

00:11:27.820 --> 00:11:31.040
This new body of literature has
produced what historian Lerna

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:34.760
Ekmekcioglu refers to
as an entangled history

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:36.660
of the late Ottoman empire.

00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:37.960
And in doing so,

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:41.620
this scholarship has made
significant contributions

00:11:41.620 --> 00:11:46.460
to both fields, but also
helped challenge this --

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:48.850
basically, this divide
between --

00:11:48.850 --> 00:11:53.560
a firm divide between
Ottoman and Armenian studies.

00:11:53.560 --> 00:11:54.860
So what I'm going
to do now is --

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:56.160
and this is what I'm going to do

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:57.460
for the remainder
of the project.

00:11:57.460 --> 00:11:58.870
I'm going to focus on the
ways in which sports can serve

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:01.820
as an under-studied lens through
which we can write an entangled

00:12:01.820 --> 00:12:03.430
history of the period.

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:04.920
And specifically, I'm going

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:08.510
to examine the ideal
masculine characteristics

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:09.810
that Ottoman Turkish

00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:14.550
and Armenian sports enthusiasts
worked out in a variety

00:12:14.550 --> 00:12:19.570
of spaces in late
Ottoman Constantinople.

00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:22.780
Now, Ottomans from a variety
of professional stripes

00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:24.960
and interests contributed
to discussions

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:28.530
about the ideal man
and his antithesis.

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:31.400
Novelists, journalists,
intellectuals,

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:33.620
as well as modernists,
all offered views

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:37.230
on the defining characteristics
of this new type of man

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:39.580
in the capitol more
specifically,

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:43.010
but also other urban centers
of the Ottoman Empire,

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:45.110
and the broader region.

00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:46.570
Now, a major contributor

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:50.830
to these discussions was the
physical culture enthusiast.

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:53.850
So during the late 19th
and early 20th Century --

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:58.090
centuries, advocates of physical
exercise and team sports argued

00:12:58.090 --> 00:13:02.440
that it wasn't sufficient for
a modern, middle-class man

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:04.380
to study secular
subjects in school.

00:13:04.380 --> 00:13:05.980
This in and of itself
was a debate.

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:08.140
But it wasn't enough to
just study secular subjects

00:13:08.140 --> 00:13:13.120
in school, learn western
languages, work in an office,

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:17.370
frequent social functions,
and dress in dapper clothes.

00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:21.990
He had to develop athletic
acumen, regularly exercise,

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:24.940
and maintain a healthy
and robust body.

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:28.680
Now, some of the earliest
contributors to discussions

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:31.810
about the importance of physical
exercise in the construction

00:13:31.810 --> 00:13:37.250
of the ideal man were educators
in a variety of Ottoman schools.

00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:40.380
It was during this period
that educators introduce

00:13:40.380 --> 00:13:43.390
and gradually institutionalize
physical education

00:13:43.390 --> 00:13:46.420
into the curriculum of a number
of different type of schools --

00:13:46.420 --> 00:13:52.020
civil and military, foreign
missionary, and a diverse array

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:54.460
of non-Muslim communal
schools --

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:58.440
Armenian, Greek,
as well as Jewish.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.020
Now, two leading institutions
were Mekhtibi Sultani

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:04.600
[phonetic], or the Imperial
School, and this is an image

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:13.170
of young men posing from
the Imperial School,

00:14:13.170 --> 00:14:14.470
and Robert College.

00:14:14.470 --> 00:14:17.230
Now, Robert College was
founded as an American college,

00:14:17.230 --> 00:14:20.750
while Mekhtibi Sultani was
based on the French lysee model,

00:14:20.750 --> 00:14:22.050
and was a government
institution.

00:14:22.050 --> 00:14:24.990
Now, Turkish and
Armenian students

00:14:24.990 --> 00:14:27.200
at both institutions
were exposed to the idea

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:30.050
that they needed to perform
physical activities in order

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:34.130
to develop strength and athletic
prowess, build character,

00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:36.600
cultivate mental and
physical disciplines,

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:39.270
as well as acquire a
competitive toughness.

00:14:39.270 --> 00:14:41.340
Educators asserted
that by exercising

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:44.160
and cultivating these
characteristics on campus,

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:46.240
students would develop
into physically, morally,

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:48.750
and spiritually sound young men.

00:14:48.750 --> 00:14:52.130
According to supporters of
sports, the regular performance

00:14:52.130 --> 00:14:56.380
of gymnastics in particular
offered multiple benefits.

00:14:56.380 --> 00:14:58.380
One of the primary
ones was a strong,

00:14:58.380 --> 00:15:01.570
defined, and healthy body.

00:15:01.570 --> 00:15:04.490
There's no debate there.

00:15:04.490 --> 00:15:06.320
Lifting weights, stretching,

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:10.170
and exercising helped
students develop a firm body,

00:15:10.170 --> 00:15:12.730
and to fight off
different types of diseases.

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:14.600
And this is the type of
language that is used

00:15:14.600 --> 00:15:16.890
in a variety of different
sources.

00:15:16.890 --> 00:15:20.900
This hygienic, beautiful body
was envisioned as a modern one.

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:22.720
Okay, so what we're doing
here -- this stands --

00:15:22.720 --> 00:15:24.460
may stand out as a
beautiful body now,

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:26.310
but what we're seeing is
the historical production

00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:27.610
of that idea.

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:30.150
And it was deemed
to be a modern body

00:15:30.150 --> 00:15:37.490
because its development required
work, discipline, and effort.

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:41.040
Now, while gymnastics were
deemed an important physical

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:45.830
activity at Mekhtibi Sultani and
many private minority schools,

00:15:45.830 --> 00:15:47.670
school officials at
foreign institutions

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:50.750
such as Robert College
were more concerned

00:15:50.750 --> 00:15:53.470
with encouraging team sports,
and forming school teams.

00:15:53.470 --> 00:15:58.560
This is the Istanbul Dodgers.

00:15:58.560 --> 00:15:59.860
That's a bad joke.

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:03.370
It's a baseball team
from Robert College.

00:16:03.370 --> 00:16:06.280
Educators believed that team
sports, such as baseball,

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:10.270
soccer, and basketball,
even moreso than gymnastics,

00:16:10.270 --> 00:16:13.220
helped students build trust in
each other, cultivate a respect

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:18.120
for rules, and develop a
commitment to teamwork.

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:23.100
Soccer and basketball's
popularity did not catch on --

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:24.750
excuse me, basketball

00:16:24.750 --> 00:16:28.210
and baseball's popularity did
not catch on, while soccer,

00:16:28.210 --> 00:16:29.510
on the other hand, did.

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:32.750
Okay. Now, another space that
advocated a distinction vision

00:16:32.750 --> 00:16:35.200
of the relationship
between physical exercise

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:38.350
and masculinity was
the sports club.

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.440
So during this period
of the late 19th

00:16:40.440 --> 00:16:42.470
and early 20th centuries,
clubs --

00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:45.370
sports clubs mushroomed
in different neighborhoods

00:16:45.370 --> 00:16:49.930
around Istanbul as spaces
where young men could exercise.

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:54.040
Now, upwardly mobile
Armenians and Turks,

00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:58.780
as well as Istanbulites from
various different backgrounds --

00:16:58.780 --> 00:17:02.060
ethno-religious backgrounds,
created and joined these clubs.

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:04.190
And this -- the emergence
of sports club is part

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:05.690
of a broader transformation,

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:07.830
and that transformation
was the creation

00:17:07.830 --> 00:17:10.910
of voluntary associations.

00:17:10.910 --> 00:17:13.210
Now, sports clubs
were predominantly,

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:16.490
although not exclusively,
spaces of male sociability.

00:17:16.490 --> 00:17:19.400
And what they did was, they
represented crucial sites

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:23.640
where historically-novel male
subjectivities were formed,

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:26.500
negotiated, and performed.

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:30.020
Now, what these spaces did
was, they attracted young --

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:32.940
likeminded and like-bodied
young men

00:17:32.940 --> 00:17:34.860
by offering them a private space

00:17:34.860 --> 00:17:37.690
where they could spend their
leisure time training their

00:17:37.690 --> 00:17:40.860
bodies, performing
sports, socializing,

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:42.180
and building homosocial bonds.

00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:45.220
So what you're also seeing is
the creation of leisure time

00:17:45.220 --> 00:17:48.580
as a space that needs
to be filled with moral,

00:17:48.580 --> 00:17:53.720
productive activities, and the
sports clubs provided this.

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:57.770
So what sports clubs did was,
they served as a testing ground,

00:17:57.770 --> 00:18:01.520
a testing ground of an emerging
middle-class masculinity

00:18:01.520 --> 00:18:05.110
in Istanbul where new
conceptions of the self,

00:18:05.110 --> 00:18:08.550
defined in relation to the
body, physical agility,

00:18:08.550 --> 00:18:11.850
a distinct look, and one's
ethno-religious community came

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:13.150
into being.

00:18:13.150 --> 00:18:14.990
Now, to a large extent,

00:18:14.990 --> 00:18:18.060
these clubs embraced
a shared civic vision

00:18:18.060 --> 00:18:21.740
of the defining characteristics
of middle-class masculinity.

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:25.570
Young men needed to regularly
exercise, compete on the pitch,

00:18:25.570 --> 00:18:29.090
maintain a well-defined
physique, regularly bathe,

00:18:29.090 --> 00:18:32.350
shave their cheeks, wear
neat and dapper attire,

00:18:32.350 --> 00:18:35.040
attend social functions,
and also read.

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:38.200
This is a litany of different
things that they needed

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.530
to embody and to perform,

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:41.880
and the sports clubs
provided the space

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:44.380
in which they accomplished this.

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:46.150
So at this -- but the same time,

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:50.920
these clubs also projected
an exclusive ethno-religious

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:54.770
understanding of
masculinity and sports.

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:57.410
So sports clubs were
established along ethnic

00:18:57.410 --> 00:19:00.820
and confessional lines,
and attracted members

00:19:00.820 --> 00:19:03.610
from a specific ethno-religious
community.

00:19:03.610 --> 00:19:05.840
And they served as spaces

00:19:05.840 --> 00:19:08.820
where young men built
ethnic-based solidarity

00:19:08.820 --> 00:19:12.410
around a popular
activity in the city.

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:14.650
Now, clubs conveyed
their shared civic

00:19:14.650 --> 00:19:16.330
and exclusive ethno-religious
reading

00:19:16.330 --> 00:19:17.840
of masculinity in
a number of ways.

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:21.250
So the main language and
symbols used, and the eponyms

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:23.970
that organizations adopted
projected a distinct

00:19:23.970 --> 00:19:25.770
ethno-religious identity.

00:19:25.770 --> 00:19:28.680
So some clubs explicitly adopted
names -- religious names,

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:31.170
excuse me, while others
were named after a heroic

00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:34.060
or mythological figure of the
club's respective community.

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:38.780
So for example, the Maccabee
Jewish Gymnastic Society

00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:41.860
[assumed spelling], the Hercules
Gymnastics Association [assumed

00:19:41.860 --> 00:19:45.480
spelling], and the Armenian
Dork Club [assumed spelling].

00:19:45.480 --> 00:19:50.510
Now, in doing so, club founders
sought to construct an awareness

00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:55.440
of the idea that the club
served as a modern fraternity

00:19:55.440 --> 00:20:00.660
of young men who were
inheritors of a deep history,

00:20:00.660 --> 00:20:04.980
a history of their
community's corporeal strength,

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:07.040
robustness, and valor.

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:14.540
Now, club uniforms, which often
featured different scripts,

00:20:14.540 --> 00:20:19.460
ethno-religious symbols, and/or
posters conveyed the idea

00:20:19.460 --> 00:20:21.040
that this was an ethnically

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:23.600
and religiously exclusive
fraternity of young men.

00:20:23.600 --> 00:20:27.570
So here we have the Besiktas
Ottoman Gymnastics Club.

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:30.420
We have Ottoman Turkish
being used, and actually,

00:20:30.420 --> 00:20:32.270
in the back -- this is
a fascinating image --

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:38.710
there's a verse from the Quran
with a bulging bicep as well.

00:20:38.710 --> 00:20:43.060
Obviously, you all have this
poster at your house [laughter].

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:46.690
And here's an image of
the Armenian Dork Club.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:54.930
The -- for -- the title
doesn't carry the same resonance

00:20:54.930 --> 00:20:59.400
that it does in Armenian,
and in English, obviously.

00:21:00.830 --> 00:21:04.730
Those Armenian speakers,
you can appreciate that.

00:21:04.730 --> 00:21:10.070
Now, a young Turkish and
Armenian man became a member

00:21:10.070 --> 00:21:12.570
of an athletic club
by agreeing to abide

00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:15.630
by the club's internal
regulations.

00:21:15.630 --> 00:21:16.930
Here are internal regulations

00:21:16.930 --> 00:21:19.140
of the Dork Armenian
Physical Training Union,

00:21:19.140 --> 00:21:21.350
and the Galatasaray
Physical Training Club.

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:24.630
And paying regular
membership fees.

00:21:24.630 --> 00:21:27.870
Now, after becoming a
member, what happened?

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:31.990
He received an identity card,
which featured his name,

00:21:31.990 --> 00:21:33.720
and the date in which
he was registered.

00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:38.090
So what you're seeing
is a cultivation of --

00:21:38.090 --> 00:21:42.820
cultivation, production, and
the performance of a self here,

00:21:42.820 --> 00:21:45.780
but also that's part of a
broader community, right?

00:21:45.780 --> 00:21:48.690
Community of the Besiktas Club,

00:21:48.690 --> 00:21:51.070
or the Armenian Dork
Club, right?

00:21:51.070 --> 00:21:54.340
Now, what did membership
provide?

00:21:54.340 --> 00:21:57.760
It enabled young men access
to the various amenities

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:03.220
that the clubs provided,
such as a gymnasium,

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:05.210
a full set of gymnastics
equipment,

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:06.930
and a shower, as well.

00:22:06.930 --> 00:22:08.500
And this is some of the ways

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:11.480
in which clubs distinguished
themselves from others, right?

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:13.150
Who had the best shower?

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:14.980
Who had the best gym?

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:16.860
I hear people laughing,
but, you know,

00:22:16.860 --> 00:22:19.720
this is serious stuff
[laughter].

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:21.020
How do you choose your gym?

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:24.330
Now, these were things
that, you know,

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:25.630
Bulsahais [assumed spelling]

00:22:25.630 --> 00:22:29.620
and other community members
were grappling with at the time.

00:22:29.620 --> 00:22:32.280
Now, membership also
enabled young men

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:34.600
to perform their
athletic dexterity

00:22:34.600 --> 00:22:36.860
in newly constructed
spaces throughout Istanbul.

00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:41.280
So basically, new, cool spaces
where people would gather,

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:45.330
such as stadiums,
gardens, and theaters.

00:22:45.330 --> 00:22:48.500
Soccer matches -- more
properly, football matches,

00:22:48.500 --> 00:22:49.800
but we're not talking
about the pigskin.

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:53.180
We're talking about the global
sport -- athletic competitions,

00:22:53.180 --> 00:22:57.160
and gymnastics exhibitions
attracted large crowds

00:22:57.160 --> 00:22:58.460
of spectators.

00:22:58.460 --> 00:23:00.040
It facilitated both intra-

00:23:00.040 --> 00:23:03.000
and inter-communal
social interactions,

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.610
and what it did was, it
celebrated the appearance

00:23:05.610 --> 00:23:12.730
of young men wearing club
uniforms and performing novel

00:23:12.730 --> 00:23:15.050
and physically challenging
activities.

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:17.730
Now, many of the
athletic events,

00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:21.740
such as the Armenian
Olympics, or [foreign word],

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:24.230
Maccabee's annual
gymnastics tournament,

00:23:24.230 --> 00:23:27.310
as well as other shows
and competitions,

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:29.440
were all organized
in the same space.

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:31.750
And this was the main space.

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:35.410
Oh, that's of the
Armenian Olympic games,

00:23:35.410 --> 00:23:38.000
but that's in the
same venue as this.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.370
This is the Union Club.

00:23:40.370 --> 00:23:43.250
And a number of these activities
maintained striking similarities

00:23:43.250 --> 00:23:44.800
as well.

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:47.410
So sports clubs,
therefore, served as spaces

00:23:47.410 --> 00:23:50.590
in which young men cultivated
distinct notions of the self.

00:23:50.590 --> 00:23:53.530
Now, central to this
identity was the commitment

00:23:53.530 --> 00:23:56.400
to a distinct understanding
of the body.

00:23:56.400 --> 00:23:59.990
Now, Turkish and Armenian
members deployed photography

00:23:59.990 --> 00:24:03.020
as a means by which they
recorded their commitment

00:24:03.020 --> 00:24:05.940
to a shared corporeal look.

00:24:05.940 --> 00:24:08.560
Members had their photographs
taken while dressing

00:24:08.560 --> 00:24:13.420
in dapper suits, starched shirts
and ties, but also as well

00:24:13.420 --> 00:24:16.420
as posing bare-chested in
order to highlight their sense

00:24:16.420 --> 00:24:17.960
of style and beautiful physique.

00:24:17.960 --> 00:24:21.290
Now, there are two images
that I want to show you.

00:24:21.290 --> 00:24:23.130
So these images --
and they're part

00:24:23.130 --> 00:24:25.640
of a broader kind
of sportsmen genre.

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:27.160
The one on the right,
but also the left --

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:33.910
and I think of them as two
sides of the same coin,

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:36.530
that young men -- upwardly
mobile young men had taken

00:24:36.530 --> 00:24:39.460
of themselves, and
also shared as tokens

00:24:39.460 --> 00:24:44.710
of friendship, and
potentially more.

00:24:44.710 --> 00:24:47.710
Now, these images provide
basically visual representations

00:24:47.710 --> 00:24:50.430
of these two interconnected
tastes and looks

00:24:50.430 --> 00:24:52.060
of the gentleman athlete,

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:54.390
which club members
celebrated and promoted.

00:24:54.390 --> 00:24:56.000
The one on the left is Ali
Sami [assumed spelling],

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.800
of the predominantly,
although not exclusively,

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:02.080
Turkish Galatasaray
Physical Training Club.

00:25:02.080 --> 00:25:04.810
And I should note, because
this is being recorded,

00:25:04.810 --> 00:25:07.270
that I'm not a Galatasaray
fan, necessarily [laughter].

00:25:07.270 --> 00:25:11.150
I appreciate that.

00:25:11.150 --> 00:25:14.130
As well as Yetvart [assumed
spelling], on the right,

00:25:14.130 --> 00:25:15.430
Shahonazar [assumed spelling]

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:17.950
of the exclusively Armenian
Artivas Physical Training Club,

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:19.250
okay?

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:21.710
Now, sports clubs served
as one of the main spaces

00:25:21.710 --> 00:25:23.910
in which Istanbulites
contributed

00:25:23.910 --> 00:25:28.620
to a broader discussion about
middle-class masculinity.

00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:31.700
However, these were
not the only sites

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:35.020
in which young men experimented
with these novel ideas.

00:25:35.020 --> 00:25:37.710
The press, for example,
was the more public --

00:25:37.710 --> 00:25:40.720
was a more public space
than the actual association.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:44.170
Now, the growth of
literacy and the mushrooming

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:47.370
of reading rooms throughout
Istanbul and other urban centers

00:25:47.370 --> 00:25:50.830
of the empire ensured that a
wider array of the citizens --

00:25:50.830 --> 00:25:53.070
excuse me, of the
empire's citizens.

00:25:53.070 --> 00:25:56.650
Not just members of athletic
associations, were visually

00:25:56.650 --> 00:25:58.420
and textually exposed
to the view

00:25:58.420 --> 00:26:01.610
that young men should regularly
exercise, perform gymnastics,

00:26:01.610 --> 00:26:03.820
and participate in team sports.

00:26:03.820 --> 00:26:05.850
So to rephrase, I
mean, think about it.

00:26:05.850 --> 00:26:09.550
You didn't have to be a
member of a club in order

00:26:09.550 --> 00:26:12.640
to see men performing in
the stadium, the theater,

00:26:12.640 --> 00:26:14.580
and the garden, but
also, you could read

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:15.880
about that in the press.

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:18.290
And these were becoming
increasingly common,

00:26:18.290 --> 00:26:20.230
both in terms of the
publication of these ideas

00:26:20.230 --> 00:26:26.290
in daily newspapers, but also
specialized magazines, okay?

00:26:26.290 --> 00:26:30.510
And now, what these publications
did, or what they constituted,

00:26:30.510 --> 00:26:33.250
at least in my estimation,
is a public forum

00:26:33.250 --> 00:26:36.070
that provided Istanbul's
growing reading public

00:26:36.070 --> 00:26:40.330
with articles focused on
particular sports, scouting,

00:26:40.330 --> 00:26:42.500
and other sport-related
leisure activities,

00:26:42.500 --> 00:26:46.000
but also on a wider array
of issues of health,

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:47.860
hygiene, and lifestyle.

00:26:47.860 --> 00:26:49.160
And what these discussions
did was,

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:53.350
they offered this aspiring
middle class with instructions

00:26:53.350 --> 00:26:56.900
and guides on how
to become young,

00:26:56.900 --> 00:27:01.890
modern men by playing sports,
having fun, exercising,

00:27:01.890 --> 00:27:03.520
and training their bodies.

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:08.180
Now, while the physical culture
press embraced shared masculine

00:27:08.180 --> 00:27:13.110
ideals, like clubs, they
also conveyed exclusive

00:27:13.110 --> 00:27:14.410
ethno-religious ties.

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:17.280
And this is accomplished
both through the languages

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:20.240
that are used, as well

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:23.960
as addressing its
reader, all right.

00:27:23.960 --> 00:27:26.630
So the fact that
Turks are addressed

00:27:26.630 --> 00:27:29.660
in an Ottoman Turkish
publication as the reader,

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:33.910
or Armenians, and specifically
Armenians from Constantinople,

00:27:33.910 --> 00:27:37.510
suggests that the ideal reader
is from this community, right?

00:27:37.510 --> 00:27:39.740
And so, what you're
having is the construction

00:27:39.740 --> 00:27:45.400
of an ideal Armenian self,
or an ideal Turkish self

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:48.760
in these publications.

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:52.070
So written by educators, leading
members and administrators

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:55.600
of sports clubs, doctors, as
well as government officials,

00:27:55.600 --> 00:27:58.460
these publications insisted on
the idea that young men needed

00:27:58.460 --> 00:28:01.590
to regularly exercise.

00:28:01.590 --> 00:28:05.690
And they needed to exercise
not just at the gym --

00:28:05.690 --> 00:28:08.560
and this is what's fascinating
about it, that you can exercise

00:28:08.560 --> 00:28:13.560
at the gym, in a
school, but also at home.

00:28:13.560 --> 00:28:16.630
So what you're having is
the broadening of the spaces

00:28:16.630 --> 00:28:19.240
in which you can
cultivate a new self.

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:23.440
Now, the sports press
regularly ran guides,

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:25.740
and here's an example
of a guide.

00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:29.010
An illustration in
text and image

00:28:29.010 --> 00:28:33.390
on the defining characteristics
of the ideal male body --

00:28:33.390 --> 00:28:36.050
proportionality, strength,

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:39.570
and health were all
treated as interconnected.

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:41.610
A person who maintained
a proportionate

00:28:41.610 --> 00:28:45.000
and defined body was
considered strong, healthy,

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.940
attentive, and disciplined.

00:28:47.940 --> 00:28:51.430
Now, in addition to indicating
acumen and competency,

00:28:51.430 --> 00:28:53.490
the proportionate, flexible,

00:28:53.490 --> 00:28:56.340
and defined male body
was treated as beautiful.

00:28:56.340 --> 00:28:57.700
And this is a really
interesting point,

00:28:57.700 --> 00:29:02.000
how the term beautiful
is not -- it's --

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:03.380
we're seeing it being gendered,

00:29:03.380 --> 00:29:05.450
but it's also applying
to men here.

00:29:05.450 --> 00:29:08.260
And you see both
the Ottoman Turkish,

00:29:08.260 --> 00:29:09.600
[foreign word] being used,

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:13.320
and [foreign word] being
used in Armenian, okay?

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:16.910
Journals soon created entire
sections for photographs

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:21.310
of semi-nude young men
run as regular features.

00:29:21.310 --> 00:29:23.620
Here are two examples.

00:29:23.620 --> 00:29:25.530
The portrait -- photographs
published

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:29.030
in these magazines
included captions,

00:29:29.030 --> 00:29:30.950
and this is what's
interesting, right.

00:29:30.950 --> 00:29:33.490
Without the captions,
these are just --

00:29:33.490 --> 00:29:38.810
these are bodies that you can't
necessarily identify whom they

00:29:38.810 --> 00:29:40.370
belong -- to whom they belong.

00:29:40.370 --> 00:29:44.770
But because they're
collated with text,

00:29:44.770 --> 00:29:46.530
what you're having
is the inscription

00:29:46.530 --> 00:29:51.290
of confessional difference
on these bodies, okay?

00:29:51.290 --> 00:29:56.070
So here is a body of Jervat Bey
[assumed spelling] on the left,

00:29:56.070 --> 00:29:58.560
and Wailim Safhibay [assumed
spelling] on the right,

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:03.390
both identified as
Ottoman Turks.

00:30:03.390 --> 00:30:08.090
This is an image of
Krikor Hagopian, and again,

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:12.020
you have the inscription on
that body as an Armenian body

00:30:12.020 --> 00:30:13.740
with the Armenian text.

00:30:13.740 --> 00:30:16.730
In addition to this, there's
a description of that body.

00:30:16.730 --> 00:30:18.860
Here's -- and the
description is the following.

00:30:18.860 --> 00:30:21.100
It refers to Levon
Hagopian [assumed spelling]

00:30:21.100 --> 00:30:22.400
and his brother.

00:30:22.400 --> 00:30:25.010
His brother's image doesn't
make an appearance next to his,

00:30:25.010 --> 00:30:29.210
and the description
is the following.

00:30:29.210 --> 00:30:31.990
"They are among the few
Armenian youth who take care

00:30:31.990 --> 00:30:35.320
of their bodies and
glorify the Armenian name

00:30:35.320 --> 00:30:40.210
through their bodies, will,
and muscle," end quote.

00:30:40.210 --> 00:30:41.760
That's an intense sentence.

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:44.830
So together, what these
images are doing is,

00:30:44.830 --> 00:30:47.180
they're establishing that
these bodies -- and again --

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:49.480
and I haven't really
talked about this yet,

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:52.390
but this is a global phenomenon
at the time, in the late 19th

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:54.910
and early 20th Century.

00:30:54.910 --> 00:30:56.210
Levon is raising his hand.

00:30:56.210 --> 00:30:57.510
He's agreeing with me.

00:30:57.510 --> 00:30:58.810
No, he's not.

00:30:58.810 --> 00:31:01.620
But these -- this image of Levon
Hagopian [assumed spelling] --

00:31:01.620 --> 00:31:04.540
and Levon is a beautiful
Bolsahai [assumed spelling] man,

00:31:04.540 --> 00:31:10.300
but that -- Levon can be found
in Paris, in New York, right,

00:31:10.300 --> 00:31:13.200
in upstate New York -- hat's
where I currently live.

00:31:13.200 --> 00:31:14.750
Saratoga Springs, Los Angeles --

00:31:14.750 --> 00:31:17.640
but it can also be
found in Bolis.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:23.530
And now, because that body
is identified in Istanbul

00:31:23.530 --> 00:31:27.870
as a beautiful body in the
imperial capitol, it's global,

00:31:27.870 --> 00:31:29.170
but it's also imperial.

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:31.760
With the text and the
publication of that body

00:31:31.760 --> 00:31:34.340
in this publication,
it's also confessional.

00:31:34.340 --> 00:31:37.960
So simultaneously, that
body is rendered global,

00:31:37.960 --> 00:31:41.100
imperial, and confessional.

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:42.910
Now, while educators

00:31:42.910 --> 00:31:45.460
in the sports press
treated physical exercise

00:31:45.460 --> 00:31:46.770
as the primary means

00:31:46.770 --> 00:31:49.740
to construct the
defining characteristics

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:53.540
of the ideal man, other
voices promised quicker

00:31:53.540 --> 00:31:56.460
and less conventional ways.

00:31:56.460 --> 00:31:59.500
Istanbul's multi-lingual
daily press is replete

00:31:59.500 --> 00:32:04.480
with advertisements for pills,
which promised to provide men

00:32:04.480 --> 00:32:07.270
with vigor and muscle.

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:10.300
So an early 20th Century
advertisement, for example,

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:11.920
addresses, quote, "those

00:32:11.920 --> 00:32:15.890
who have lost the strength
of youth," end quote.

00:32:15.890 --> 00:32:17.650
So these are pills that promise

00:32:17.650 --> 00:32:20.790
to provide people
strength, okay?

00:32:20.790 --> 00:32:26.530
Now, other products sought to
help men who were impotent.

00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:29.810
Strong, beautiful, and
healthy men were supposed

00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:32.270
to have a strong sex drive.

00:32:32.270 --> 00:32:36.930
So -- I know it's a
shock to all of us here.

00:32:36.930 --> 00:32:40.090
Here's an a-historical
statement that I'm making.

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:43.730
Impotence was a sign
of weakness, okay?

00:32:43.730 --> 00:32:46.520
Now, Amrita [assumed spelling]
-- this is a publication --

00:32:46.520 --> 00:32:52.230
excuse me, a type of -- an ad,
and a product, served as one

00:32:52.230 --> 00:32:54.500
of the most well-known
products that promised

00:32:54.500 --> 00:32:58.450
to restore the virility to
all impotent men of all ages

00:32:58.450 --> 00:33:02.820
in the capitol who, quote,
"conduct a regular life,

00:33:02.820 --> 00:33:05.140
but silently suffer from the
mistakes of their youth."

00:33:05.140 --> 00:33:08.370
And we can hear dun, dun, dun.

00:33:08.370 --> 00:33:11.120
Amrita ran identical
advertisements

00:33:11.120 --> 00:33:14.630
in Ottoman Turkish,
Armenian, Greek,

00:33:14.630 --> 00:33:19.930
and French daily newspapers in
order to reach these poor souls

00:33:19.930 --> 00:33:24.890
in the -- in the capitol, who
were all afflicted by these --

00:33:24.890 --> 00:33:27.110
who were all afflicted
by impotency.

00:33:27.110 --> 00:33:29.940
And here's the --
here are the ads.

00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:33.200
Now, these two advertisements
publish an identical caricature

00:33:33.200 --> 00:33:36.760
of an dapperly dressed gentleman
and the following headline.

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:40.160
"Only for men, an important
announcement for those

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:43.080
who have lost the
strength of the body."

00:33:43.080 --> 00:33:44.590
Now, the advertisement is --

00:33:44.590 --> 00:33:49.520
you know it opens a really
interesting question about,

00:33:49.520 --> 00:33:50.820
you know, marketing.

00:33:50.820 --> 00:33:53.010
I don't know how successful
they were, because there's a lot

00:33:53.010 --> 00:33:57.480
of text here, but the
text is very rich,

00:33:57.480 --> 00:34:01.150
in terms of what it
-- it goes on to talk

00:34:01.150 --> 00:34:05.650
about how people actually
become impotent, what are some

00:34:05.650 --> 00:34:08.390
of the immoral activities
that they engage in.

00:34:08.390 --> 00:34:10.740
Alcohol is one of them.

00:34:10.740 --> 00:34:14.370
Gambling is one of them,
and, I should warn you,

00:34:14.370 --> 00:34:19.330
dark and thick tea -- and tea
as well, according to Amrita.

00:34:19.330 --> 00:34:23.500
So if you have had a lot of tea
and coffee today, you may want

00:34:23.500 --> 00:34:26.330
to look into Amrita [laughter].

00:34:26.330 --> 00:34:29.170
Okay? According to the product.

00:34:29.170 --> 00:34:30.670
Now, it goes on.

00:34:30.670 --> 00:34:33.860
It says, "I have prepared a
miraculous and effective pill

00:34:33.860 --> 00:34:35.700
that will give hope
and joy to those

00:34:35.700 --> 00:34:37.830
who are afflicted by impotency.

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:40.020
This pill that I have
invented will heal the health

00:34:40.020 --> 00:34:42.130
of those men who have
been completely weakened

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:45.430
because of bad practices, or
have been under the infrequence

00:34:45.430 --> 00:34:47.830
of unfavorable circumstances."

00:34:47.830 --> 00:34:49.660
Keeps that kind of broad.

00:34:49.660 --> 00:34:53.050
"This cure that I have invented
is a blessing for everyone.

00:34:53.050 --> 00:34:56.590
It gives everyone
health and strength."

00:34:56.590 --> 00:34:59.710
Now, what's going on here?

00:34:59.710 --> 00:35:03.510
At first glance, gymnastics
guides and advertisements

00:35:03.510 --> 00:35:05.110
for pills and tonics published

00:35:05.110 --> 00:35:07.460
in Istanbul's multi-lingual
press seem

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:09.930
to be fundamentally different.

00:35:09.930 --> 00:35:14.220
However, I would argue they
maintain striking similarities.

00:35:14.220 --> 00:35:16.850
They all -- they're
all concerned

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:19.720
with helping men
rejuvenate their bodies.

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:22.660
And as a result, they
provide an insightful window

00:35:22.660 --> 00:35:28.350
into the diverging approaches
that educators, writers,

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:32.970
manufacturers, and
advertisers proposed

00:35:32.970 --> 00:35:37.240
that the ideal man adopt
in order to be a strong,

00:35:37.240 --> 00:35:39.610
beautiful, and virile body.

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:42.450
Now, moreover, these conflicting
approaches constituted an

00:35:42.450 --> 00:35:45.850
emerging market, which treated
the body as a central site

00:35:45.850 --> 00:35:47.360
of male subject formation.

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:52.220
Now, in conclusion, the writings
of educators about sports,

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:55.620
physical culture, the
activities of club members --

00:35:55.620 --> 00:35:57.830
they all demonstrate that
young men articulated

00:35:57.830 --> 00:35:59.650
and performed their
gendered identity

00:35:59.650 --> 00:36:03.390
by cultivating a defined body
and regularly exercising,

00:36:03.390 --> 00:36:07.080
and were reading about exercise
in late Ottoman Istanbul.

00:36:07.080 --> 00:36:11.720
Together, sports, sports clubs,
and the press served as spaces

00:36:11.720 --> 00:36:14.820
where Istanbulites from
a variety of backgrounds,

00:36:14.820 --> 00:36:17.860
including Armenian and
Turkish, experimented

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:20.330
with new conceptions
of the self.

00:36:20.330 --> 00:36:22.080
Now, while I have demonstrated

00:36:22.080 --> 00:36:25.050
that Ottomans espouse similar
views about the importance

00:36:25.050 --> 00:36:27.710
of physical exercise,
techniques of the body,

00:36:27.710 --> 00:36:32.070
and athletic acumen, I have also
attempted to highlight the fact

00:36:32.070 --> 00:36:35.250
that Ottomans worked out
these ideas within spaces

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:37.790
that projected exclusive
ethno-religious ties,

00:36:37.790 --> 00:36:41.870
and that were firmly divided
along confessional lines.

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:45.720
Thus, these clubs and the press
might've embraced the share

00:36:45.720 --> 00:36:49.760
masculine ideal, but they
also cultivated an exclusive

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:53.710
ethno-religious identity among
their readers and members.

00:36:53.710 --> 00:36:57.450
Now, this, I want to stress,
should not be interpreted

00:36:57.450 --> 00:37:00.300
as contradictory, at
least in my estimation.

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:03.260
On the contrary, I think
it invites us to examine --

00:37:03.260 --> 00:37:06.180
and I'm speaking
to all historians

00:37:06.180 --> 00:37:08.020
of the time period, really.

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:10.290
It invites us to examine
the ways in which Turks

00:37:10.290 --> 00:37:14.720
and Armenians experimented with
and shaped the defining contours

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:17.830
of other novel practices,
beliefs,

00:37:17.830 --> 00:37:20.170
and norms within the boundaries

00:37:20.170 --> 00:37:21.840
of ethno-religious
communal spaces

00:37:21.840 --> 00:37:24.470
in a late imperial session.

00:37:24.470 --> 00:37:26.510
Thank you for your attention.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:32.900
[ Applause ]

00:37:32.900 --> 00:37:34.650
&gt;&gt; Levon Avdoyan:
Thank you, Dr. Yildiz.

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:44.650
Our next speaker is a dear
friend of mine, and a colleague

00:37:44.650 --> 00:37:50.240
of many, many years, Theo van
Lint, who is the professor

00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:53.820
of Armenian studies
at Oxford University.

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:59.380
He has chosen one of my favorite
poets of the 20th Century --

00:37:59.380 --> 00:38:03.760
as a matter of fact, one of my
favorite Armenian poets ever.

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:07.480
His talk is on "Poetry,
Patria, and Pedigree,

00:38:07.480 --> 00:38:13.250
Eghishe Charents' Monuments
and the Muse's Discontent."

00:38:13.250 --> 00:38:14.610
&gt;&gt; Theo marten van
Lint: Thank you, Levon,

00:38:14.610 --> 00:38:19.170
for organizing this
wonderful gathering.

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:24.470
I am sorely tempted to
do 10 pushups before I --

00:38:24.470 --> 00:38:27.870
[laughter] before
I start [laughter].

00:38:29.270 --> 00:38:31.850
From the poetry of
the body to the poetry

00:38:31.850 --> 00:38:35.460
of the Muse's Discontent,
so -- [laughter].

00:38:37.250 --> 00:38:39.180
Thank you very much.

00:38:39.180 --> 00:38:43.700
Yes, so you see, friendship
blossoms in many ways,

00:38:43.700 --> 00:38:46.040
and leads to all
kinds of things.

00:38:47.820 --> 00:38:52.070
"Poetry, Patria, and Pedigree,
Eghishe Charents' Monument,

00:38:52.070 --> 00:38:54.330
and the Muse's Discontent."

00:38:54.330 --> 00:38:57.610
A poem rarely exists
entirely on its own,

00:38:57.610 --> 00:39:02.010
revealed by divine inspiration
without any cultural context.

00:39:02.010 --> 00:39:04.980
Almost every aspect of it
exists thanks to a network

00:39:04.980 --> 00:39:08.200
of conventions, applied
and tweaked anew

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:12.110
in a never-ending flow
of creative activity.

00:39:12.110 --> 00:39:14.830
These carefully-chosen
conventions carry particular

00:39:14.830 --> 00:39:17.500
meaning, and their application
by poets through space

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:20.260
and time is potentially
very powerful,

00:39:20.260 --> 00:39:22.830
as they place their
work both in a tradition

00:39:22.830 --> 00:39:25.020
and in their own
contemporary context.

00:39:25.020 --> 00:39:28.680
My contribution today
addresses this double phenomenon

00:39:28.680 --> 00:39:32.060
of conventionality and
contextualization through a poem

00:39:32.060 --> 00:39:35.710
by the Armenian modernist
poet, Eghishe Charents.

00:39:35.710 --> 00:39:38.410
It was the poem that
triggered these considerations,

00:39:38.410 --> 00:39:40.110
not the phenomena addressed.

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:43.560
For me, the source of the study
of literature is the text,

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:48.250
from which all else follows.

00:39:48.250 --> 00:39:51.710
In January 1934, Charents
finished a poem called

00:39:51.710 --> 00:39:54.920
"Monument" in Armenian,
which is a first indication

00:39:54.920 --> 00:39:56.720
that something particular
is going on.

00:39:56.720 --> 00:40:00.300
So "Monument" -- the poet could
have called it [foreign word],

00:40:00.300 --> 00:40:03.900
the usual and indigenous
Armenian word.

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:08.590
Why use a word that had clear
western and ancient overtones?

00:40:08.590 --> 00:40:10.650
In fact, it hails
back to a famous poem

00:40:10.650 --> 00:40:14.310
by the Latin poet Horace
that is [foreign word],

00:40:14.310 --> 00:40:17.380
written just over
2000 years ago.

00:40:17.380 --> 00:40:21.910
Its opening line
is [foreign word],

00:40:21.910 --> 00:40:25.790
"I erected a monument
more durable than bronze."

00:40:25.790 --> 00:40:29.200
The connotation with classical
imperial commemoration is

00:40:29.200 --> 00:40:32.970
visually present as
well, as you can see.

00:40:32.970 --> 00:40:36.680
The date is in Roman letters, in
literally monumental capitals.

00:40:36.680 --> 00:40:38.680
They are not Armenian
ones, which are used

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:41.900
to indicate numbers as well,
as you know, or Arabic numbers,

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:44.770
as is common in the western
world, and as it was also

00:40:44.770 --> 00:40:47.570
in the Soviet Union, where
Charents wrote his poem.

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:50.810
Yet, the reference
is not direct.

00:40:50.810 --> 00:40:54.350
It does not bridge 2000
years without intermediary,

00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:57.510
because the opening words of
Horace's poem, [foreign word],

00:40:57.510 --> 00:41:01.800
are the motto of a famous
Russian poem Eghishe Charents

00:41:01.800 --> 00:41:03.100
knew very well.

00:41:03.100 --> 00:41:06.980
It was written in -- a
Century earlier, in 1836,

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:11.080
by Russia's national poet,
Alexander Sergeyevich Pushkin.

00:41:11.080 --> 00:41:12.510
This is its opening line.

00:41:12.510 --> 00:41:18.710
[foreign word], "I erected
a monument for myself,

00:41:18.710 --> 00:41:21.400
not made by human hands."

00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:23.140
What's going on here?

00:41:23.140 --> 00:41:25.640
I'd like to spend the time
allotted to this talk trying

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:28.180
to suggest some answers
to this question.

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:29.810
First, let us look at the poems.

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:31.110
That's always the most fun.

00:41:31.110 --> 00:41:34.760
Latin, Russian, and Armenian --
I began with the Armenian one.

00:41:34.760 --> 00:41:37.510
So here it is, "Monument."

00:41:37.510 --> 00:42:24.060
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:42:24.060 --> 00:42:26.600
Twelfth of January, 1934.

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:31.500
In English -- whoops, this
is the young Charents,

00:42:31.500 --> 00:42:38.500
more or less, returned from the
fighting around Van in 1915.

00:42:38.500 --> 00:42:41.870
This is Charents as he may have
looked when he wrote the poem.

00:42:41.870 --> 00:42:46.780
And this is the English
translation.

00:42:46.780 --> 00:42:50.730
"I erected a monument for
myself in a difficult age --

00:42:50.730 --> 00:42:52.580
" in a fraught age, perhaps --

00:42:52.580 --> 00:42:54.730
"when everything was
going to ruin around me,

00:42:54.730 --> 00:42:57.240
that for many years, for
centuries, had stood,

00:42:57.240 --> 00:43:00.200
and had seemed immortal
in the world.

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:03.500
I wove my monument out of
songs profound and complex,

00:43:03.500 --> 00:43:06.270
from thoughts that are red
hot anew, that carry life

00:43:06.270 --> 00:43:08.790
in themselves, that can
flow in gushing forth

00:43:08.790 --> 00:43:11.610
from the fiery heart of my age.

00:43:11.610 --> 00:43:12.940
I was born in Kars.

00:43:12.940 --> 00:43:16.800
However, in my soul, the song
of Iran was always a flame,

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:20.650
like an old native yearning
unquenched, but the native land

00:43:20.650 --> 00:43:24.790
of my soul became
the entire world."

00:43:24.790 --> 00:43:28.570
This is an image of the Church
of the 12 Apostles in Kars,

00:43:28.570 --> 00:43:33.070
with the elevated
castle in the background.

00:43:33.070 --> 00:43:34.980
You can just about see it.

00:43:34.980 --> 00:43:36.730
Now we go back 2000 years.

00:43:36.730 --> 00:43:46.330
This is a newspaper photograph
of Horace declaiming his poem

00:43:46.330 --> 00:43:48.780
in front of his audience.

00:43:48.780 --> 00:43:52.450
I will read this in Latin

00:43:52.450 --> 00:43:57.150
in a very approximate
meter, I must say.

00:43:57.150 --> 00:44:00.530
It's not simple to follow this.

00:44:00.530 --> 00:44:02.140
So I will make mistakes.

00:44:02.140 --> 00:44:04.510
Let it be recorded.

00:44:04.510 --> 00:44:53.500
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:44:53.500 --> 00:44:57.750
And this is another 19th Century
impression of Horace, you see,

00:44:57.750 --> 00:45:03.200
wearing the laurels
of the poet king.

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:06.200
The English translation here,

00:45:06.200 --> 00:45:10.980
which will give us some more
insight, is by Ted Loker,

00:45:10.980 --> 00:45:14.570
taken from the all-present
internet.

00:45:14.570 --> 00:45:17.640
"I have created a monument
more lasting than bronze,

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:20.530
and higher than the royal
site of the pyramids,

00:45:20.530 --> 00:45:24.320
which neither harsh rains nor
the wild north wind can erode,

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:26.220
nor the countless
succession of years,

00:45:26.220 --> 00:45:28.300
and the flight of the seasons.

00:45:28.300 --> 00:45:31.090
I will not entirely
die, and a large part

00:45:31.090 --> 00:45:33.000
of me will avoid the grave.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:37.250
Constantly renewed, I will grow
in the eyes of posterity so long

00:45:37.250 --> 00:45:41.890
as the Pontifex and the solemn
Vestal visit the Capitoline.

00:45:41.890 --> 00:45:44.620
Where the River Aufidus
roars, and where Daunus

00:45:44.620 --> 00:45:47.630
in the dry summers,
ruled his rural folk, I,

00:45:47.630 --> 00:45:51.380
risen to greatness from humble
beginnings, will be renowned

00:45:51.380 --> 00:45:54.060
as the first to adapt
the Aeolian verses

00:45:54.060 --> 00:45:56.250
to Italian meters.

00:45:56.250 --> 00:45:58.560
Take the well-deserved
pride, Melpomene,

00:45:58.560 --> 00:46:04.610
and freely grant me the wreath
of Apollo for my crown."

00:46:04.610 --> 00:46:07.000
Personal fame and prowess

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:10.550
as poets are central
to Horace's poem.

00:46:10.550 --> 00:46:13.040
Horace is one of the
most-quoted classical authors

00:46:13.040 --> 00:46:15.540
in western civilization.

00:46:15.540 --> 00:46:21.090
The Dutch big dictionary has
250 quotations from his work

00:46:21.090 --> 00:46:24.530
that phonated into
21st-Century Dutch.

00:46:24.530 --> 00:46:26.730
The reason for his fame,
however, does not lie

00:46:26.730 --> 00:46:28.240
in the fact that
he was the first

00:46:28.240 --> 00:46:30.400
to put Greek verse
into Latin meter.

00:46:30.400 --> 00:46:33.830
That is of less importance
to us than it was to him.

00:46:33.830 --> 00:46:36.070
To trace the itinerary
of Horace's work

00:46:36.070 --> 00:46:39.240
of almost two millennia
is not my intention here,

00:46:39.240 --> 00:46:42.690
nor can I trace the particular
root the Horace reception took

00:46:42.690 --> 00:46:43.990
in Russia.

00:46:43.990 --> 00:46:47.120
But through 18th Century ground
tours and enlightenment context,

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:49.540
including the strong
presence of French literature,

00:46:49.540 --> 00:46:51.660
as well as their
school curriculum,

00:46:51.660 --> 00:46:54.800
well-educated youngsters
like Alexander Pushkin --

00:46:54.800 --> 00:46:57.060
or Sasha Pushkin, as he
would've been then --

00:46:57.060 --> 00:46:59.950
would have gained
knowledge of the classics.

00:46:59.950 --> 00:47:02.250
And here is Pushkin.

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:15.510
And he is again, without Getty.

00:47:15.510 --> 00:48:26.120
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:27.420
And [inaudible].

00:48:27.420 --> 00:48:34.440
"I've raised myself a monument
not made by human hands.

00:48:34.440 --> 00:48:37.460
The path of the people to
it will never grow over.

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:40.550
Its insubordinate
hat has risen higher

00:48:40.550 --> 00:48:42.630
than the Alexandrian pillar.

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:44.270
No, I shall not fully die.

00:48:44.270 --> 00:48:47.350
The soul in my faithful
lyre shall survive my dust,

00:48:47.350 --> 00:48:51.900
and shall escape putrefaction,
and I shall be famous wherever

00:48:51.900 --> 00:48:55.500
in the sub-lunar world
even a single poet lives.

00:48:55.500 --> 00:48:59.200
Tidings of me will go out over
all great Rus -- " Russia --

00:48:59.200 --> 00:49:01.940
"and every tribe in every
tongue will name me,

00:49:01.940 --> 00:49:04.380
the proud descendant
of the Slavs, the Finn,

00:49:04.380 --> 00:49:08.650
the Tungus who is now savage,
and the steppe-loving Kalmyk.

00:49:08.650 --> 00:49:12.760
And for long shall I
remain loved by the people,

00:49:12.760 --> 00:49:15.660
for awakening noble
feelings with my lyre,

00:49:15.660 --> 00:49:19.570
because in my cruel age, I have
celebrated freedom and called

00:49:19.570 --> 00:49:21.610
for pity to the fallen.

00:49:21.610 --> 00:49:24.550
Oh, muse, be obedient
to the command of God.

00:49:24.550 --> 00:49:26.480
Do not be fearful of abuse.

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:28.480
Do not demand a crown.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:31.580
Accept both praise and
slander with indifference,

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:35.080
and don't dispute with fools."

00:49:36.430 --> 00:49:38.840
This is Pushkin, what
he may have looked

00:49:38.840 --> 00:49:43.170
like in 1836, by Pyotr Sokolov.

00:49:43.170 --> 00:49:46.830
The translation of this
poem is by Catriona Kelly,

00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:49.870
professor of Russian at Oxford,
who makes it a central pillar

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:52.020
of her admirable, very
short introduction

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:53.890
to Russian literature.

00:49:53.890 --> 00:49:57.950
One may wonder, what binds these
particular three poems together,

00:49:57.950 --> 00:50:01.470
so wide apart in time and space?

00:50:01.470 --> 00:50:05.140
The interrelationship between
poems mentioned at the opening

00:50:05.140 --> 00:50:07.050
of this presentation
and the trivial fact

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:09.610
of temporal sequence
give partial answers.

00:50:09.610 --> 00:50:11.990
Charents built from Pushkin,
who built from Horace,

00:50:11.990 --> 00:50:13.290
while Charents was, himself,

00:50:13.290 --> 00:50:16.130
part of the Russian-language
reception of Horace.

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:21.080
Charents, the communist Armenian
poet, was raised on the Russian

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:25.380
and western European culture,
apart from the Armenian one.

00:50:25.380 --> 00:50:28.130
The Latin poetic tradition does
not have a strong reception

00:50:28.130 --> 00:50:32.250
in Armenian literature, quite
in distinction to the Greek one,

00:50:32.250 --> 00:50:34.530
which is overwhelmingly
present from the beginning

00:50:34.530 --> 00:50:38.140
of the Armenian written
tradition in the fifth Century.

00:50:38.140 --> 00:50:41.350
It was only from the early
modern period onwards,

00:50:41.350 --> 00:50:42.720
through the highly successful

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:46.320
and culturally savvy Armenian
merchants, as we have seen,

00:50:46.320 --> 00:50:48.480
and the Catholic
Armenian Methodist fathers

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:51.470
that [inaudible] and post
[inaudible] European classical

00:50:51.470 --> 00:50:54.680
reception entered
Armenian literature.

00:50:54.680 --> 00:50:57.580
In the poems, a set of
binary oppositions seem

00:50:57.580 --> 00:51:02.520
to present themselves -- poet
and patron, poetry and politics,

00:51:02.520 --> 00:51:05.200
native region and the wider
world, and the direction

00:51:05.200 --> 00:51:07.440
from local to
world-encompassing.

00:51:07.440 --> 00:51:09.730
And two more construed
ones, perhaps,

00:51:09.730 --> 00:51:13.810
fame versus civilization,
and the combination of poetry

00:51:13.810 --> 00:51:17.880
with freedom over against
empire and oppression.

00:51:17.880 --> 00:51:20.520
The latter opposition makes
itself more clearly heard

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:24.310
in Pushkin and Charents
than in Horace.

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:26.990
The life and work of all
three poets was defined,

00:51:26.990 --> 00:51:30.520
to some extent, by a
patron, with all the shades

00:51:30.520 --> 00:51:32.940
that word can muster, Maecenas.

00:51:32.940 --> 00:51:35.850
This literally was the name
of the protector-become-friend

00:51:35.850 --> 00:51:38.710
of the down and out Horace,
who was superbly gifted

00:51:38.710 --> 00:51:42.330
but financially broke after he
had sided with the Republicans

00:51:42.330 --> 00:51:44.100
in the Civil War
following the murder

00:51:44.100 --> 00:51:46.400
of Caesar -- Julius Caesar.

00:51:46.400 --> 00:51:49.260
Horace had received the best
possible education in Rome,

00:51:49.260 --> 00:51:53.070
and then in Athens among
the elite of the empire.

00:51:53.070 --> 00:51:56.010
Horace was then introduced by
Virgil, the other great poet,

00:51:56.010 --> 00:51:58.470
to Maecenas, who
gave him a villa,

00:51:58.470 --> 00:52:00.890
and thus the leisure
to write quietly.

00:52:00.890 --> 00:52:02.190
I would like that [laughter].

00:52:02.190 --> 00:52:06.400
Ere long, Augustus, the
emperor, offered him a position

00:52:06.400 --> 00:52:09.590
as his personal secretary,
which he refused.

00:52:09.590 --> 00:52:14.030
He also kept intrusions into his
independence by Maecenas at bay.

00:52:14.030 --> 00:52:15.750
This is a paradigmatic example

00:52:15.750 --> 00:52:18.450
of the way artistic independence
is maintained in the need

00:52:18.450 --> 00:52:21.230
of patronage, and how
recognition can be an even

00:52:21.230 --> 00:52:23.020
greater threat to it.

00:52:23.020 --> 00:52:25.830
Being Augustus' personal
secretary would've left him

00:52:25.830 --> 00:52:28.740
neither the leisure to
write, nor, one must assume,

00:52:28.740 --> 00:52:30.430
the freedom to choose
his own themes.

00:52:30.430 --> 00:52:31.930
I mean, this is 2000 years ago.

00:52:31.930 --> 00:52:36.130
It's still very actual.

00:52:36.130 --> 00:52:39.710
Directly comparable are the
cases of Pushkin and Charents.

00:52:39.710 --> 00:52:42.060
The latter was embraced
by the socialist system

00:52:42.060 --> 00:52:44.810
with state and art patronage.

00:52:44.810 --> 00:52:48.300
Pushkin was a small
aristocrat of mixed heritage.

00:52:48.300 --> 00:52:50.610
He also received the
best possible education,

00:52:50.610 --> 00:52:55.550
the elite lysee of [inaudible],
followed by a life dedicated

00:52:55.550 --> 00:52:58.820
to poetry and court
cavorting, or carousal.

00:52:58.820 --> 00:53:03.540
However, Pushkin's outspokenness
soon earned him exile.

00:53:03.540 --> 00:53:07.310
Then, his poetic career took
a turn, evoking Horace's fate.

00:53:07.310 --> 00:53:10.320
Following the Decembrist
uprising of 1825,

00:53:10.320 --> 00:53:13.780
Pushkin was interrogated
by the Tsar in person.

00:53:13.780 --> 00:53:16.330
The poet came out
with honor intact,

00:53:16.330 --> 00:53:17.970
but had to accept the favor

00:53:17.970 --> 00:53:20.840
of the emperor's
personal censorship.

00:53:20.840 --> 00:53:22.790
In practice, this
meant subjection

00:53:22.790 --> 00:53:27.560
to Count Alexander Benckendorff,
founder of the secret police,

00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:30.430
precursor of the KGB,
to the an institution

00:53:30.430 --> 00:53:34.210
that might lend him another
term of exile, or worse.

00:53:34.210 --> 00:53:37.870
We find echoes of this in
one line in Pushkin's poem.

00:53:37.870 --> 00:53:40.660
You may wonder which one.

00:53:40.660 --> 00:53:46.080
[foreign word], "in my cruel
age, I have celebrated freedom."

00:53:46.080 --> 00:53:47.690
This line recurs, in fact,

00:53:47.690 --> 00:53:50.410
in the opening line
of Charents' poem.

00:53:50.410 --> 00:53:52.940
Nothing here about the
quality of the monument,

00:53:52.940 --> 00:53:56.520
as in Horace's more durable than
bronze, and Pushkin's not made

00:53:56.520 --> 00:54:00.150
by human hands, which by the
way is a reference to ikons,

00:54:00.150 --> 00:54:02.670
that are not made
by human hands.

00:54:02.670 --> 00:54:07.910
But "I erected a monument for
myself in a difficult age,"

00:54:07.910 --> 00:54:11.480
followed by the devastating,
dystopian lines allowing

00:54:11.480 --> 00:54:14.120
for an interpretation
denouncing the revolution he had

00:54:14.120 --> 00:54:17.510
so enthusiastically
embraced two decades earlier,

00:54:17.510 --> 00:54:21.080
as well as mourning
the genocide of 1915.

00:54:21.080 --> 00:54:23.460
"When everything was
going to ruin around me

00:54:23.460 --> 00:54:25.720
that for many years, for
centuries, had stood,

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:30.060
and that seemed immortal in the
world" -- the end of tradition,

00:54:30.060 --> 00:54:32.160
the end of immortality.

00:54:32.160 --> 00:54:36.760
Does Charents predict his
own immortality instead?

00:54:36.760 --> 00:54:39.900
The last minutes allotted
to me, I would like to spend

00:54:39.900 --> 00:54:41.400
on Charents' trajectory --

00:54:41.400 --> 00:54:43.700
in particular, a brief
consideration of the state

00:54:43.700 --> 00:54:50.850
of the art of poetry, and by
extension, but flowing from it,

00:54:50.850 --> 00:54:54.880
the value of the word
in today's society.

00:54:54.880 --> 00:54:58.100
Where we stand, there seems
ample reason for caution,

00:54:58.100 --> 00:55:01.210
seeing the value of the
word in politics here

00:55:01.210 --> 00:55:04.460
in the United States,
in the United Kingdom,

00:55:04.460 --> 00:55:05.760
and in my native Europe.

00:55:05.760 --> 00:55:07.830
Where it is difficult
to find people capable

00:55:07.830 --> 00:55:11.230
to unite the remnants of
humanistic culture based

00:55:11.230 --> 00:55:14.510
on the Greek Judeo-Christian
tradition into a vision

00:55:14.510 --> 00:55:18.150
for the continent in danger
of caving in once again

00:55:18.150 --> 00:55:20.880
to ignorant populism
and rampant nationalism.

00:55:20.880 --> 00:55:25.200
Here, the muse's discontent
comes to the fore in full force,

00:55:25.200 --> 00:55:28.530
as it had in Pushkin's
and Charents' poems.

00:55:28.530 --> 00:55:32.870
For we must be aware of the fact
that both our disenchantments

00:55:32.870 --> 00:55:35.640
of Horace's triumphant
proclamation of a victory

00:55:35.640 --> 00:55:38.360
of poetry over politics,
and more generally,

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:39.840
of culture over politics --

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:43.210
after all, he had erected
a monument more durable

00:55:43.210 --> 00:55:47.140
than bronze, the stuff
emperor's statues are made of.

00:55:47.140 --> 00:55:49.380
He might just as well have
mentioned the word marmer --

00:55:49.380 --> 00:55:50.680
marble.

00:55:50.680 --> 00:55:55.690
Moreover, if Pushkin's laconic
final advice to the muse,

00:55:55.690 --> 00:56:01.190
and to himself, [foreign word],
"and don't' dispute with fools,"

00:56:01.190 --> 00:56:04.380
betrays a trust in rational
persuasion, in Charents,

00:56:04.380 --> 00:56:06.950
we find a completely
different emphasis,

00:56:06.950 --> 00:56:08.870
one that in my view
is now more actual

00:56:08.870 --> 00:56:14.120
than it has been for some time.

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:16.080
[foreign word], "the native land

00:56:16.080 --> 00:56:19.460
of my soul became
the entire world."

00:56:19.460 --> 00:56:23.300
This is both a return
to Goethe's ideal

00:56:23.300 --> 00:56:25.340
of [foreign word],
world literature,

00:56:25.340 --> 00:56:28.030
and one to socialist -- to
the socialist international,

00:56:28.030 --> 00:56:31.960
if you want -- an overcoming of
nationalism and limiting origins

00:56:31.960 --> 00:56:35.710
in a forward-looking movement
towards a better world.

00:56:35.710 --> 00:56:37.220
Much could be said about this,

00:56:37.220 --> 00:56:39.910
as it represents a typical
Charentsian paradox,

00:56:39.910 --> 00:56:41.990
in particular in
his later years.

00:56:41.990 --> 00:56:44.710
The communists denouncing
totalitarianism,

00:56:44.710 --> 00:56:47.930
and the cosmopolitan atheists
returning to the religious great

00:56:47.930 --> 00:56:51.070
of his native Armenian
tradition, [foreign word],

00:56:51.070 --> 00:56:54.390
even more appreciated by him.

00:56:54.390 --> 00:56:56.170
Possibly an understandable
preference,

00:56:56.170 --> 00:56:58.450
given the free poet's
temperament,

00:56:58.450 --> 00:57:01.540
but this is not the time
and place to go into that.

00:57:01.540 --> 00:57:04.360
What does need to be noted
is the seemingly veering away

00:57:04.360 --> 00:57:06.540
from poetics to psychology.

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:09.290
Charents gives pride
of place to the soul.

00:57:09.290 --> 00:57:12.630
In fact, what happens here is,
on the one hand, a consequence

00:57:12.630 --> 00:57:16.140
of the socialist realist forging
of new souls, interpreted,

00:57:16.140 --> 00:57:21.270
one is tempted to say, without
the encumbrance of ideology.

00:57:21.270 --> 00:57:24.290
Of that, Charents had, by now,
become more than a little wary,

00:57:24.290 --> 00:57:26.110
of which the opening stanza

00:57:26.110 --> 00:57:28.570
of the poem eloquently
bears witness.

00:57:28.570 --> 00:57:30.580
On the other, it is a
consequence of the power

00:57:30.580 --> 00:57:33.360
of the alternative to the
ideology of nationalism,

00:57:33.360 --> 00:57:35.390
the dire consequences of
which he had witnessed

00:57:35.390 --> 00:57:38.300
in a genocidal attempt by the
Ottoman Turkish government

00:57:38.300 --> 00:57:40.490
at the annihilation
of his people

00:57:40.490 --> 00:57:43.180
under cover of World War I.

00:57:43.180 --> 00:57:45.640
Precisely how the whole
world became the native land

00:57:45.640 --> 00:57:48.130
of his soul is intriguing,
because that is

00:57:48.130 --> 00:57:51.380
through the poetry, through
the power of the word.

00:57:51.380 --> 00:57:54.860
Therefore, no veering away, in
fact, from poetry after all,

00:57:54.860 --> 00:57:56.680
but the strengthening
of the bond

00:57:56.680 --> 00:57:59.610
between poetry and personality.

00:57:59.610 --> 00:58:01.870
The last years of Charents
life, in particular,

00:58:01.870 --> 00:58:03.860
bear eloquent witness to this.

00:58:03.860 --> 00:58:05.730
He set out on a journey
of absorption

00:58:05.730 --> 00:58:09.420
and creative expression while
his life was in constant peril.

00:58:09.420 --> 00:58:12.260
His work was taken away
from him, as were his wife

00:58:12.260 --> 00:58:15.120
and children, and soon, his
health and freedom as well,

00:58:15.120 --> 00:58:16.840
followed by death in prison.

00:58:16.840 --> 00:58:19.500
The pressure must
have been unbearable.

00:58:19.500 --> 00:58:25.840
On 28th March, 1937, he writes,
in quiet recognition of the fact

00:58:25.840 --> 00:58:30.470
that he turned 40, and had
been a poet for 25 years,

00:58:30.470 --> 00:58:34.560
"I am celebrating my double
jubilee, alone, and persecuted,

00:58:34.560 --> 00:58:38.140
a poet exiled in
his own fatherland."

00:58:38.140 --> 00:58:41.300
The late Charents awaits
deeper exploration,

00:58:41.300 --> 00:58:43.930
and offers both pearls
and cups of bitterness.

00:58:43.930 --> 00:58:46.950
The philological situation
of his later work is very,

00:58:46.950 --> 00:58:49.380
very difficult, due to the
fact that it had to be buried

00:58:49.380 --> 00:58:51.500
in the ground, and
we don't have anyone

00:58:51.500 --> 00:58:54.480
to tell us how he
would have liked

00:58:54.480 --> 00:58:56.310
to have eventually edited it.

00:58:56.310 --> 00:58:59.670
And so we have various
editions of his work

00:58:59.670 --> 00:59:06.610
that bear no relationship to one
another, nor a real account --

00:59:06.610 --> 00:59:12.140
accountability of how
these are represented.

00:59:12.140 --> 00:59:16.020
There is a parallel
with the work

00:59:16.020 --> 00:59:17.900
of Osit Mumbo Schtum
[assumed spelling].

00:59:17.900 --> 00:59:22.080
However, Osit Mumbo Schtum's
widow knew everything by heart,

00:59:22.080 --> 00:59:24.430
and knew what he had
wanted to do with it.

00:59:24.430 --> 00:59:27.870
So there was a big
difference there as well.

00:59:27.870 --> 00:59:30.400
In 1937, Charents was somber

00:59:30.400 --> 00:59:33.200
about what he proclaimed
in his monument.

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:36.470
It had been -- despite the
clearly disillusioned tone,

00:59:36.470 --> 00:59:39.770
at least been partially
triumphant.

00:59:39.770 --> 00:59:45.370
So he says, and there are
five separate lines published

00:59:45.370 --> 00:59:48.510
together, in one case with
the fifth one lacking --

00:59:48.510 --> 01:00:16.770
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

01:00:16.770 --> 01:00:19.890
-- "you were born null
and void, like a number

01:00:19.890 --> 01:00:22.190
with a zero overlooked.

01:00:22.190 --> 01:00:23.730
In Kars, you may have been born,

01:00:23.730 --> 01:00:26.030
but the world was
your fatherland.

01:00:26.030 --> 01:00:27.760
Kars, and Maku [assumed
spelling], and the world --

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:29.990
which was your land, poet?

01:00:29.990 --> 01:00:35.160
Kars, and Maku, and the world --
all of it was your land, poet.

01:00:35.160 --> 01:00:37.180
Woe to you, Charents,
either way.

01:00:37.180 --> 01:00:41.690
Neither your song nailed
it, nor your life."

01:00:41.690 --> 01:00:43.270
Charents' restlessness

01:00:43.270 --> 01:00:45.370
in his final years
does not seem directed

01:00:45.370 --> 01:00:47.550
at the realization
of a political ideal.

01:00:47.550 --> 01:00:51.210
It has become clear that the
communist experiment is both a

01:00:51.210 --> 01:00:53.740
farce and drenched in blood.

01:00:53.740 --> 01:00:56.930
The poet's remaining energy is
directed at two areas of life,

01:00:56.930 --> 01:00:59.370
it seems, and this
needs checking --

01:00:59.370 --> 01:01:02.640
poetry, and the exploration
of religions, always engaged

01:01:02.640 --> 01:01:04.510
for the good of humanity.

01:01:04.510 --> 01:01:07.500
What the conclusion has to
be about the relationship

01:01:07.500 --> 01:01:10.680
between poetry and politics
is unclear so far, for me.

01:01:10.680 --> 01:01:12.900
A political system
that murdered poets

01:01:12.900 --> 01:01:16.590
by the dozens clearly took the
poet word extremely seriously,

01:01:16.590 --> 01:01:20.850
feared it, and tried to kill
poet and destroy poetry itself.

01:01:20.850 --> 01:01:24.570
Poetry is a means to find truth,
to insist on honesty in life

01:01:24.570 --> 01:01:27.910
and society, forms part of the
wider endeavor to speak truth

01:01:27.910 --> 01:01:32.420
to power, beginning with
oneself -- truth to oneself.

01:01:32.420 --> 01:01:35.290
Dire experience stripped
Charents of all pretense,

01:01:35.290 --> 01:01:37.680
and in the end, what
remained was the word,

01:01:37.680 --> 01:01:40.210
the word that had also been
there in the beginning.

01:01:40.210 --> 01:01:46.970
A contemporary of Charents,
W.H. Auden, in January 1939,

01:01:46.970 --> 01:01:49.670
commemorating the death
of William Butler Yeats,

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:51.290
wrote three poems, in the second

01:01:51.290 --> 01:01:54.050
of which the following
movement occurs.

01:01:54.050 --> 01:01:56.250
"Poetry makes nothing happen.

01:01:56.250 --> 01:02:00.350
It survives in the valley of
its making, flows on south

01:02:00.350 --> 01:02:03.530
from ranches of isolation
and the busy griefs,

01:02:03.530 --> 01:02:06.290
raw towns that we
believe and die in.

01:02:06.290 --> 01:02:10.370
It survives, a way of
happening, a mouth."

01:02:10.370 --> 01:02:14.100
Auden finishes the third and
final poem as a blind song,

01:02:14.100 --> 01:02:17.670
in assured way keeping intact a
belief of the power of the word

01:02:17.670 --> 01:02:21.340
as life-creating, and
as a life-giving gift.

01:02:21.340 --> 01:02:24.620
You probably know it.

01:02:24.620 --> 01:02:26.370
It's a fantastic poem.

01:02:26.370 --> 01:02:27.670
"Follow, poet.

01:02:27.670 --> 01:02:29.390
Follow right to the
bottom of the night.

01:02:29.390 --> 01:02:31.630
With your own constraining
voice,

01:02:31.630 --> 01:02:34.110
still persuade us to rejoice.

01:02:34.110 --> 01:02:37.650
With the farming of a verse,
make a vineyard of the curse.

01:02:37.650 --> 01:02:41.380
Sing of human unsuccess
in a rapture of distress.

01:02:41.380 --> 01:02:45.000
In the deserts of the heart,
let the healing fountain start.

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:49.610
In the prison of his days, teach
the free man how to praise."

01:02:49.610 --> 01:02:52.390
Such was the monument erected.

01:02:52.390 --> 01:02:56.610
Did Charents seek to fathom
similar deep wellsprings?

01:02:56.610 --> 01:02:58.510
Thank you.

01:02:58.510 --> 01:03:07.730
[ Applause ]

01:03:07.730 --> 01:03:09.030
&gt;&gt; Levon Avdoyan:
Thank you, Theo.

01:03:09.030 --> 01:03:10.330
Please do not break your leg.

01:03:10.330 --> 01:03:17.190
Yes. We should've had
stairs on this side, too.

01:03:17.190 --> 01:03:20.920
Again, my thanks for that
wonderful talk on Charents,

01:03:20.920 --> 01:03:24.930
and now we go from friend to
friend and scholar to scholar.

01:03:24.930 --> 01:03:31.300
And a denizen of Washington,
D.C., and the director

01:03:31.300 --> 01:03:33.970
of analytical support and
production staff in the Bureau

01:03:33.970 --> 01:03:37.520
of Intelligence and Research
of the Department of State,

01:03:37.520 --> 01:03:40.800
Robert Krikorian, who will
speak on the "Re-appropriation

01:03:40.800 --> 01:03:43.190
of the Past, History
and Politics

01:03:43.190 --> 01:03:48.230
in Soviet Armenia, 1988-1991."

01:03:49.570 --> 01:03:51.060
&gt;&gt; Robert Krikorian:
Thank you very much.

01:03:51.060 --> 01:03:53.730
As a government employee,
I have to start

01:03:53.730 --> 01:03:55.040
with my standard disclaimer

01:03:55.040 --> 01:03:57.600
that my views do not
reflect those views

01:03:57.600 --> 01:04:00.210
of the U.S. government,
and that will probably come

01:04:00.210 --> 01:04:02.630
as no surprise [laughter].

01:04:02.630 --> 01:04:07.090
Let me first really give
a most sincere thank-you

01:04:07.090 --> 01:04:10.940
to my dear friend,
Levon Avdoyan.

01:04:10.940 --> 01:04:16.630
Levon has been a friend and
a mentor for 32 years now,

01:04:16.630 --> 01:04:21.700
having met in 1986 when I first
made it down to Washington,

01:04:21.700 --> 01:04:25.380
D.C. So I have learned
a tremendous amount,

01:04:25.380 --> 01:04:28.640
both from him personally and
from all the wonderful programs

01:04:28.640 --> 01:04:30.820
that he has put on
through the Library

01:04:30.820 --> 01:04:32.120
of Congress, so thank you.

01:04:32.120 --> 01:04:34.490
Thank you, Mary Jane.

01:04:34.490 --> 01:04:40.360
What I would like to do
today is tell a few stories,

01:04:40.360 --> 01:04:42.420
and some of the stories
that I will tell,

01:04:42.420 --> 01:04:44.450
some of you have lived through.

01:04:44.450 --> 01:04:47.040
And some of you have
helped me with my research,

01:04:47.040 --> 01:04:50.430
like my dear friend,
Nerses Hayrapetyan.

01:04:50.430 --> 01:04:55.800
So what I am going to do is to
look at the role of history,

01:04:55.800 --> 01:04:58.860
how history is remembered,
and the role that played

01:04:58.860 --> 01:05:02.520
in undermining communist
legitimacy in Soviet Armenia

01:05:02.520 --> 01:05:06.430
from the years 1988 to 1991.

01:05:06.430 --> 01:05:08.670
This is part of a much larger
project that I undertook,

01:05:08.670 --> 01:05:10.310
but what I would
like to do for today

01:05:10.310 --> 01:05:13.740
for a few minutes is
extract the parts that relate

01:05:13.740 --> 01:05:15.150
to how the first Republic

01:05:15.150 --> 01:05:18.730
of Armenia was remembered
in Soviet Armenia.

01:05:18.730 --> 01:05:21.560
Because this is being
the 100th anniversary

01:05:21.560 --> 01:05:23.690
of the Independent
Republic of Armenia,

01:05:23.690 --> 01:05:26.960
I thought it might
be a good pairing.

01:05:26.960 --> 01:05:29.440
In terms of context,
let me just say

01:05:29.440 --> 01:05:32.950
that I had the extraordinary
good fortune of living

01:05:32.950 --> 01:05:37.610
in Soviet Armenia
from 1988 to 1991,

01:05:37.610 --> 01:05:41.450
during the last three
years of soviet rule.

01:05:41.450 --> 01:05:44.110
I got to Soviet Armenia
through a program

01:05:44.110 --> 01:05:46.590
that the soviet government
had organized

01:05:46.590 --> 01:05:49.260
for all ethnic Armenians abroad

01:05:49.260 --> 01:05:52.610
to get an education
in Soviet Armenia.

01:05:52.610 --> 01:05:55.030
Now, I did not need
a soviet education.

01:05:55.030 --> 01:05:58.690
I had an American education that
I was perfectly satisfied with,

01:05:58.690 --> 01:06:01.060
but I did not speak Armenian.

01:06:01.060 --> 01:06:05.670
So I went to learn Armenian,
and it so happened to coincide

01:06:05.670 --> 01:06:08.020
with the -- really
the renaissance

01:06:08.020 --> 01:06:09.880
of the Armenian nation.

01:06:09.880 --> 01:06:12.550
And so, for three
years, I got to witness.

01:06:12.550 --> 01:06:14.100
I got to participate.

01:06:14.100 --> 01:06:17.650
I got to observe, and I
got to gather lots and lots

01:06:17.650 --> 01:06:19.250
of material along the way

01:06:19.250 --> 01:06:22.740
that I was never quite sure
what I was going to do with.

01:06:22.740 --> 01:06:25.570
But I knew that what I was
witnessing was important,

01:06:25.570 --> 01:06:28.230
and so when I went back to
graduate school later in life

01:06:28.230 --> 01:06:31.100
to write a doctoral
dissertation, I used a lot

01:06:31.100 --> 01:06:34.690
of that material to try to
make sense of what had happened

01:06:34.690 --> 01:06:38.350
in Armenia in those
three very short,

01:06:38.350 --> 01:06:40.830
but very, very intense years.

01:06:40.830 --> 01:06:42.850
Right? We have a sweep
of Armenian history

01:06:42.850 --> 01:06:47.060
that goes back millennia, but in
that very short period of time

01:06:47.060 --> 01:06:52.580
from 1988 to 1991, the
whole world changed.

01:06:52.580 --> 01:06:55.350
Not just Armenia, but
the whole world changed.

01:06:55.350 --> 01:06:58.640
No one predicted the
collapse of the Soviet Union,

01:06:58.640 --> 01:07:00.900
except for someone
named Andrei Amalrik,

01:07:00.900 --> 01:07:02.940
who wrote a book <i>Will
the Soviet Union Last</i>

01:07:02.940 --> 01:07:05.830
<i>Until 1980 -- Survive
Until 1984 </i>.

01:07:05.830 --> 01:07:07.840
Unfortunately, he
died before that,

01:07:07.840 --> 01:07:11.240
before the Soviet
Union fell in 1991,

01:07:11.240 --> 01:07:14.990
so he didn't even get
a chance to see that.

01:07:14.990 --> 01:07:19.320
What I would like to do is
talk a little bit about --

01:07:19.320 --> 01:07:22.210
again, to contextualize
about historical narratives,

01:07:22.210 --> 01:07:24.030
and the role that they play.

01:07:24.030 --> 01:07:26.410
They're really the --
kind of the cornerstones

01:07:26.410 --> 01:07:29.100
of anyone's identity, right?

01:07:29.100 --> 01:07:31.710
We have narratives in
the United States, right?

01:07:31.710 --> 01:07:33.680
The words we use matter.

01:07:33.680 --> 01:07:36.770
They connote either
where we stand socially,

01:07:36.770 --> 01:07:40.120
economically, or politically.

01:07:40.120 --> 01:07:42.830
Interestingly, in the Soviet
Union, history was one

01:07:42.830 --> 01:07:47.630
of the first things that the
soviet state appropriated.

01:07:47.630 --> 01:07:54.060
Imagine 1917 to the -- you know,
when the revolution broke out,

01:07:54.060 --> 01:07:59.780
and then the following years of
civil war, foreign intervention.

01:07:59.780 --> 01:08:03.690
The soviet state -- the
Bolshevik party was fighting

01:08:03.690 --> 01:08:06.060
for its very survival.

01:08:06.060 --> 01:08:09.120
Yet, it devoted very limit --
its very limited resources --

01:08:09.120 --> 01:08:13.520
it devoted a considerable amount
of resources to making sure

01:08:13.520 --> 01:08:16.380
that it controlled
the historical record.

01:08:16.380 --> 01:08:18.400
It created something
called [foreign word],

01:08:18.400 --> 01:08:21.920
a party committee
devoted to history,

01:08:21.920 --> 01:08:24.370
and devoted to making sure

01:08:24.370 --> 01:08:31.040
that the narrative supported the
ideological goals of the state.

01:08:31.040 --> 01:08:34.920
So what that means is
that, in the Armenian case,

01:08:34.920 --> 01:08:41.760
Armenia inherited the soviet
system, the soviet ethos,

01:08:41.760 --> 01:08:46.680
if you will, but they never
accepted it wholeheartedly.

01:08:46.680 --> 01:08:49.730
And there was always a
little pushback, right?

01:08:49.730 --> 01:08:52.230
There was always
a little tension

01:08:52.230 --> 01:08:55.710
between what the soviet
central authorities wanted,

01:08:55.710 --> 01:09:00.510
and what the Armenian Soviet
Socialist Republic actually did.

01:09:00.510 --> 01:09:02.590
So I think there
are two quotes --

01:09:02.590 --> 01:09:05.330
and we don't have the
makeup artist here to try

01:09:05.330 --> 01:09:09.390
to dampen the moisture, but
hopefully that won't come

01:09:09.390 --> 01:09:11.000
out too badly on film.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:16.630
There's two quotes that
I would like to use.

01:09:16.630 --> 01:09:17.930
In the Soviet Union,

01:09:17.930 --> 01:09:22.200
every profession had a
professional journal.

01:09:22.200 --> 01:09:26.730
If you were a tractor driver in
Ufa, you had your own journal.

01:09:26.730 --> 01:09:29.240
If you were a tube
player in Krasnoyarsk,

01:09:29.240 --> 01:09:30.720
you had your own journal.

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:33.380
Well, the historians had their
own journals, too, right,

01:09:33.380 --> 01:09:35.910
and one of them was called
[foreign word], "Problems

01:09:35.910 --> 01:09:38.230
or Questions of History."

01:09:38.230 --> 01:09:42.140
And every issue started with an
editorial, right, and that kind

01:09:42.140 --> 01:09:46.510
of laid out what the party
line would be for that issue,

01:09:46.510 --> 01:09:49.130
and kind of where
soviet history stood.

01:09:49.130 --> 01:09:53.280
So there's a wonderful quote
from 1960, and it says,

01:09:53.280 --> 01:09:57.700
"The study of history has
never been a mere curiosity,

01:09:57.700 --> 01:10:01.480
a withdrawal into the past
for the sake of the past.

01:10:01.480 --> 01:10:02.940
Historical science --

01:10:02.940 --> 01:10:05.080
" and everything for
them was a science, so --

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:07.890
"historical science
has been, and remains,

01:10:07.890 --> 01:10:11.720
an arena of sharp
ideological conflict."

01:10:11.720 --> 01:10:14.610
Now, perhaps more indicative
of this approach would be

01:10:14.610 --> 01:10:19.160
from Nikita Khrushchev, who
had a reputation, let's say,

01:10:19.160 --> 01:10:22.000
for being somewhat more
earthy in his pronouncements,

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:26.270
and he declared that "Historians
are dangerous people.

01:10:26.270 --> 01:10:28.560
They are capable of
upsetting everything.

01:10:28.560 --> 01:10:29.860
They must be directed."

01:10:29.860 --> 01:10:36.880
So that is the backdrop for
what I will now present,

01:10:36.880 --> 01:10:40.900
and I have my clock here.

01:10:40.900 --> 01:10:42.970
Tell me, what time would
you like me to stop?

01:10:42.970 --> 01:10:47.070
It is 2:26.

01:10:47.070 --> 01:10:51.060
Okay. So, the reassessment
of history at the end

01:10:51.060 --> 01:10:54.970
of soviet rule in Armenia -- it
didn't take place in isolation.

01:10:54.970 --> 01:10:58.540
It occurred simultaneously
with and as an integral part

01:10:58.540 --> 01:11:02.540
of unprecedented
political, economic, social,

01:11:02.540 --> 01:11:04.770
and intellectual changes
that were taking place,

01:11:04.770 --> 01:11:09.150
a result of Gorbachev's
policies of Glasnost.

01:11:09.150 --> 01:11:12.100
Developments in any one of these
spheres -- political, economic,

01:11:12.100 --> 01:11:15.540
social, intellectual --
influenced the nature and pace

01:11:15.540 --> 01:11:19.320
of change in the others in
an interconnected process

01:11:19.320 --> 01:11:23.290
that culminated in the collapse
of soviet power in Armenia,

01:11:23.290 --> 01:11:26.300
and the reestablishment
of an independent state.

01:11:26.300 --> 01:11:30.130
These processes, in turn, were
deeply influenced by events

01:11:30.130 --> 01:11:34.310
in other parts of the Soviet
Union and eastern European.

01:11:34.310 --> 01:11:36.360
Mikhail Gorbachev's policy

01:11:36.360 --> 01:11:40.260
of Glasnost gave
the initial impetus

01:11:40.260 --> 01:11:42.360
to a more open discussion

01:11:42.360 --> 01:11:46.090
of the problems facing
soviet Armenian society.

01:11:46.090 --> 01:11:48.810
These early discussions,
which focused on topics

01:11:48.810 --> 01:11:52.650
of contemporary relevance,
such as the environment,

01:11:52.650 --> 01:11:54.960
the state of education
in the republic,

01:11:54.960 --> 01:11:58.350
the status of the Armenian
language, Armenian culture,

01:11:58.350 --> 01:12:02.240
also included an important
historical component,

01:12:02.240 --> 01:12:05.070
as Armenians strove to
understand the origins

01:12:05.070 --> 01:12:08.710
of the problems affecting
their society.

01:12:08.710 --> 01:12:12.470
The search for the roots of
environmental, educational,

01:12:12.470 --> 01:12:13.770
and cultural questions

01:12:13.770 --> 01:12:17.490
in Armenia inevitably
involved the study of history.

01:12:17.490 --> 01:12:22.080
For example, environmental
degradation was traced back

01:12:22.080 --> 01:12:25.020
to the industrialization
policies of Stalin,

01:12:25.020 --> 01:12:28.020
which led to a closer look
at Stalin's other policies

01:12:28.020 --> 01:12:31.980
in Armenia, including the
drawing of borders and the loss

01:12:31.980 --> 01:12:35.950
of Karabakh and Nakhchevan
to Azerbaijan.

01:12:35.950 --> 01:12:39.200
The exploration of these
issues soon gave way

01:12:39.200 --> 01:12:42.900
to a more broadly-based
reevaluation of the soviet

01:12:42.900 --> 01:12:46.660
and pre-soviet Armenian
historical experience.

01:12:46.660 --> 01:12:49.900
The emphasis on historical
issues was of more

01:12:49.900 --> 01:12:51.830
than just academic interest.

01:12:51.830 --> 01:12:54.600
It had political
implications as well.

01:12:54.600 --> 01:12:57.880
Historical interpretation in
Armenia was given relevance

01:12:57.880 --> 01:13:01.420
in February of 1988 with
the spontaneous formation

01:13:01.420 --> 01:13:04.480
of a mass social movement
throughout Armenia agitating

01:13:04.480 --> 01:13:05.780
for the secession

01:13:05.780 --> 01:13:08.320
of the Nagorno-Karabakh
autonomous district

01:13:08.320 --> 01:13:12.440
from Azerbaijan, and its
unification with Armenia.

01:13:12.440 --> 01:13:14.890
The borders of Nagorno-Karabakh
were established

01:13:14.890 --> 01:13:19.150
in the early 1920s with the
direct participation of Stalin,

01:13:19.150 --> 01:13:21.310
who arranged for the
region to be placed

01:13:21.310 --> 01:13:24.850
under the administration
of soviet Azerbaijan.

01:13:24.850 --> 01:13:29.010
It was this perceived
historical injustice

01:13:29.010 --> 01:13:32.970
that mobilized the Armenians
into action, with the hope

01:13:32.970 --> 01:13:35.230
that under Glasnost,
a rectification

01:13:35.230 --> 01:13:37.680
of borders might be possible.

01:13:37.680 --> 01:13:40.220
Using history as a means
to demonstrate the justice

01:13:40.220 --> 01:13:44.780
of their cause, Armenians began
to draw wider historical lessons

01:13:44.780 --> 01:13:47.130
from their experiences
in the pre-soviet

01:13:47.130 --> 01:13:51.320
and early soviet periods, which
steadily led to the undermining

01:13:51.320 --> 01:13:53.880
of soviet legitimacy in Armenia.

01:13:53.880 --> 01:13:58.700
In order to increase
their chances

01:13:58.700 --> 01:14:02.370
of resolving the Karabakh
issue to their satisfaction,

01:14:02.370 --> 01:14:04.440
Armenians turned to
history to demonstrate

01:14:04.440 --> 01:14:07.830
that the region was historically
Armenian, and should be placed

01:14:07.830 --> 01:14:09.890
under the control of Yerevan.

01:14:09.890 --> 01:14:12.430
They pointed to the involvement
of Stalin and the injustice

01:14:12.430 --> 01:14:15.020
that had occurred under soviet
Azerbaijani administration

01:14:15.020 --> 01:14:16.630
throughout the years.

01:14:16.630 --> 01:14:19.080
This instrumental use of
history by the Armenians

01:14:19.080 --> 01:14:21.890
in 1988 was just the beginning

01:14:21.890 --> 01:14:25.600
of a full-fledged historical
reassessment of Armenia's past,

01:14:25.600 --> 01:14:28.590
the outcome of which would
have profound implications

01:14:28.590 --> 01:14:31.020
for the entire nation.

01:14:31.020 --> 01:14:34.070
The process of historical
reassessment was fundamentally

01:14:34.070 --> 01:14:38.570
altered by the February-March
pogrom against Armenians

01:14:38.570 --> 01:14:42.100
in the Azerbaijani
industrial city of Sumqayit.

01:14:42.100 --> 01:14:45.580
That event, more than any
other, changed the course

01:14:45.580 --> 01:14:48.370
of events in soviet Armenia.

01:14:48.370 --> 01:14:54.120
It broke a tacit social contract
between the soviet state

01:14:54.120 --> 01:14:57.180
and the Armenian people,
which had been in place

01:14:57.180 --> 01:15:00.300
since the early days
of soviet rule.

01:15:00.300 --> 01:15:03.570
This social contract
assured Armenian acquiescence

01:15:03.570 --> 01:15:08.010
to soviet rule in exchange
for the physical security

01:15:08.010 --> 01:15:10.730
and protection from the Turks,

01:15:10.730 --> 01:15:14.790
Armenia's most serious
security threat.

01:15:14.790 --> 01:15:18.420
Although this might not
seem like much of a bargain,

01:15:18.420 --> 01:15:21.700
it must be viewed in the context
of the atrocities perpetrated

01:15:21.700 --> 01:15:25.860
against Armenians in the
Ottoman Empire in 1915.

01:15:25.860 --> 01:15:29.320
Despite the atrocities committed
under Lenin and Stalin,

01:15:29.320 --> 01:15:32.030
they never reached the
same level of intensity.

01:15:32.030 --> 01:15:34.730
This geopolitical reality
allowed Armenians to come

01:15:34.730 --> 01:15:37.520
to terms with soviet
rule in their country.

01:15:37.520 --> 01:15:41.780
The memory of 1915 was kept
alive throughout the years

01:15:41.780 --> 01:15:45.450
of soviet rule by
survivors, by scholars,

01:15:45.450 --> 01:15:49.360
and by the intense feelings
of the general public.

01:15:49.360 --> 01:15:50.660
The persistent denial

01:15:50.660 --> 01:15:52.690
by successive Turkish
governments only served

01:15:52.690 --> 01:15:55.140
to deepen the importance
Armenians attached

01:15:55.140 --> 01:15:56.440
to their national tragedy.

01:15:56.440 --> 01:16:01.030
The events at Sumqayit had a
profound impact on Armenians,

01:16:01.030 --> 01:16:05.510
and resurrected painful
historical memories and images.

01:16:05.510 --> 01:16:08.800
The close ethnic and linguistic
ties between Azerbaijanis

01:16:08.800 --> 01:16:11.980
and Turks only served to
reinforce the connection

01:16:11.980 --> 01:16:15.900
between the two events in
the minds of most Armenians.

01:16:15.900 --> 01:16:19.100
Sumqayit occurred so
close to the beginning

01:16:19.100 --> 01:16:22.450
of the democratic movement in
Armenia that it is impossible

01:16:22.450 --> 01:16:25.850
for this event not to
indelibly mark the course

01:16:25.850 --> 01:16:28.200
of the movement from the outset.

01:16:28.200 --> 01:16:30.750
Thus, from the very beginning,
the struggle over Karabakh,

01:16:30.750 --> 01:16:34.310
and the creation of a national
democratic movement in Armenia,

01:16:34.310 --> 01:16:36.700
perception of current
events was colored

01:16:36.700 --> 01:16:38.870
by an understanding of the past.

01:16:38.870 --> 01:16:41.120
And conversely, a
particular reading

01:16:41.120 --> 01:16:43.510
of the past influenced the ways

01:16:43.510 --> 01:16:46.990
in which the present
was seen and understood.

01:16:46.990 --> 01:16:51.850
History and politics,
inextricably linked in Armenia

01:16:51.850 --> 01:16:55.950
in the years leading up to the
dissolution of the Soviet Union,

01:16:55.950 --> 01:16:59.860
and the interconnection between
the two played a leading role

01:16:59.860 --> 01:17:03.180
in the determination
to secede from the USSR

01:17:03.180 --> 01:17:05.360
and reestablish an
independent state.

01:17:05.360 --> 01:17:10.040
The interpreters of the Armenian
past were not just historians,

01:17:10.040 --> 01:17:12.760
but intellectuals
more generally.

01:17:12.760 --> 01:17:15.040
And their deconstruction
of the soviet narrative,

01:17:15.040 --> 01:17:19.610
so laboriously fabricated over
70 years of communist control,

01:17:19.610 --> 01:17:22.040
would prove decisive
in the process

01:17:22.040 --> 01:17:24.670
of redefining Armenian
national identity,

01:17:24.670 --> 01:17:28.100
and laying the groundwork for a
post-soviet Armenian identity.

01:17:28.100 --> 01:17:32.150
Through the use of the mass
media and publishing houses,

01:17:32.150 --> 01:17:35.940
Armenian historians and other
intellectuals reshaped popular

01:17:35.940 --> 01:17:40.380
perception of the past, which
in turn influenced the present.

01:17:40.380 --> 01:17:41.680
The reassessment of history

01:17:41.680 --> 01:17:44.770
in Armenia was neither
completely elite-driven,

01:17:44.770 --> 01:17:48.280
nor did it emanate
exclusively from below.

01:17:48.280 --> 01:17:51.930
Instead, it was a symbiotic
process, in which historians

01:17:51.930 --> 01:17:54.290
and other intellectuals
commenced

01:17:54.290 --> 01:17:57.820
with a wide-ranging debate
about the past at the same time

01:17:57.820 --> 01:18:00.730
that the general reading
public was getting excited

01:18:00.730 --> 01:18:04.850
about the fresh interpretations
made possible by Glasnost.

01:18:04.850 --> 01:18:09.040
Popular interest in the past
meshed with a renewed interest

01:18:09.040 --> 01:18:11.690
and renewed spirit
of scholarly inquiry,

01:18:11.690 --> 01:18:13.940
as historians began
the dismantling

01:18:13.940 --> 01:18:16.180
of soviet revisionism.

01:18:16.180 --> 01:18:18.490
This resulted in nothing
less than a revolution

01:18:18.490 --> 01:18:21.650
in thinking among soviet
Armenians about themselves,

01:18:21.650 --> 01:18:23.790
and their place in the world.

01:18:23.790 --> 01:18:27.030
Having become accustomed over
the years to be skeptical

01:18:27.030 --> 01:18:29.860
of the heavy-handed
soviet approach to history,

01:18:29.860 --> 01:18:33.030
the Armenian reading public
greeted Glasnost warmly,

01:18:33.030 --> 01:18:34.330
and showed great interest

01:18:34.330 --> 01:18:36.680
in the new interpretation
of their past.

01:18:36.680 --> 01:18:39.700
Armenian skepticism,
in part, was a result

01:18:39.700 --> 01:18:42.060
of the clumsy nature
of soviet revisionism.

01:18:42.060 --> 01:18:46.640
It was also the result of the
extensive use of oral history

01:18:46.640 --> 01:18:49.230
in Armenia as the elder
generations passed

01:18:49.230 --> 01:18:51.700
down to the younger
generation memories

01:18:51.700 --> 01:18:56.420
of a pre-soviet and
non-soviet past.

01:18:56.420 --> 01:19:00.930
Discussion of the independent
1918 to 1920 pre-soviet Republic

01:19:00.930 --> 01:19:05.090
of Armenia was closely connected
to and occurred simultaneously

01:19:05.090 --> 01:19:09.310
with reinterpretation of events
such as the liberation movement,

01:19:09.310 --> 01:19:12.580
the Armenian Genocide,
et cetera.

01:19:12.580 --> 01:19:15.070
This was understandable, as
many of the leading figures

01:19:15.070 --> 01:19:16.830
of the liberation movement went

01:19:16.830 --> 01:19:20.400
on to play leading roles during
the independent republic.

01:19:20.400 --> 01:19:23.530
And of course, the foundation
of the republic occurred

01:19:23.530 --> 01:19:26.970
in the midst of war
and revolution.

01:19:26.970 --> 01:19:30.410
Armenia became a soviet
republic in December 1920,

01:19:30.410 --> 01:19:34.910
as a result of a joint
soviet-Turkish assault.

01:19:34.910 --> 01:19:38.040
The new Bolshevik rulers
inherited a devastated

01:19:38.040 --> 01:19:39.810
and exhausted country,

01:19:39.810 --> 01:19:42.490
and needed to quickly
establish their legitimacy

01:19:42.490 --> 01:19:45.130
and consolidate their rule.

01:19:45.130 --> 01:19:47.760
One method of legitimizing
their rule was

01:19:47.760 --> 01:19:51.130
to employ a tactic perfected
throughout all the lands

01:19:51.130 --> 01:19:53.280
of the former Russian Empire.

01:19:53.280 --> 01:19:57.210
This was to discredit
and delegitimize the rule

01:19:57.210 --> 01:19:59.130
of the predecessor regime --

01:19:59.130 --> 01:20:02.430
in this case, the Armenian
Revolutionary Federation.

01:20:02.430 --> 01:20:05.950
As Marxists, the new soviet
leaders found the ideology

01:20:05.950 --> 01:20:09.760
of the Armenian nationalists
anathema, and they lost no time

01:20:09.760 --> 01:20:14.020
in leading the -- in labeling
the dashnaks as, quote unquote,

01:20:14.020 --> 01:20:17.570
"bourgeois nationalists,
imperialist lackeys,

01:20:17.570 --> 01:20:22.420
narrow-minded chauvinists, and
irresponsible adventurers."

01:20:22.420 --> 01:20:25.520
They blamed the dashnaks for
the loss of independence,

01:20:25.520 --> 01:20:27.580
and credited the Bolsheviks
with, quote unquote,

01:20:27.580 --> 01:20:30.140
"saving Armenians
from the destruction

01:20:30.140 --> 01:20:32.270
at the hands of the Turks."

01:20:32.270 --> 01:20:34.900
By thus discrediting
the previous regime,

01:20:34.900 --> 01:20:37.920
the soviets were able to gloss
over the uncomfortable fact

01:20:37.920 --> 01:20:41.680
that they had allied with the
Turks who were responsible

01:20:41.680 --> 01:20:44.790
for massacring Armenians,
and then jointly invaded

01:20:44.790 --> 01:20:47.150
and occupied an independent
state.

01:20:47.150 --> 01:20:50.410
The Bolshevik alliance
with the nationalist forces

01:20:50.410 --> 01:20:53.130
of Mustafa Kemal was
completely ignored

01:20:53.130 --> 01:20:56.970
in soviet historiography, while
the alleged voluntary reunion

01:20:56.970 --> 01:21:00.430
of Armenia and Russia
was stressed instead.

01:21:00.430 --> 01:21:01.960
The soviets portrayed
the leaders

01:21:01.960 --> 01:21:03.710
of the independent republic

01:21:03.710 --> 01:21:05.970
as inexperience bourgeois
nationalists

01:21:05.970 --> 01:21:09.630
who understood nothing about
governance, and who were blinded

01:21:09.630 --> 01:21:13.920
to the reality of Armenia's
dire situation by the promises

01:21:13.920 --> 01:21:16.500
of the western capitalist
powers.

01:21:16.500 --> 01:21:20.080
They accused Armenia of being
an outpost of imperialism

01:21:20.080 --> 01:21:21.380
that was used to weaken

01:21:21.380 --> 01:21:23.970
and undermine the socialist
revolution in Russia,

01:21:23.970 --> 01:21:28.760
and drive an artificial wedge
between the working classes

01:21:28.760 --> 01:21:30.060
of Armenia and Russia.

01:21:30.060 --> 01:21:31.510
It's probably important to note

01:21:31.510 --> 01:21:34.390
that Armenia really didn't have
a working class at this point,

01:21:34.390 --> 01:21:39.260
but we don't have to digress too
far to see the contradictions.

01:21:39.260 --> 01:21:41.630
The lack of information
and supression of knowledge

01:21:41.630 --> 01:21:44.940
in Armenia regarding the
independent republic served

01:21:44.940 --> 01:21:46.920
soviet interests
in several ways.

01:21:46.920 --> 01:21:50.810
First, it allowed the soviets
to present the republic

01:21:50.810 --> 01:21:55.020
as an experiment that failed
because of the inexperience

01:21:55.020 --> 01:21:58.190
and immaturity of its
leaders, and their inability

01:21:58.190 --> 01:22:01.650
to prevent the hostile
takeover by Turkey.

01:22:01.650 --> 01:22:03.540
According to the soviet
version of events,

01:22:03.540 --> 01:22:05.910
the adventurous dashnaks
had initiated a war

01:22:05.910 --> 01:22:07.760
against the Turks, which ended

01:22:07.760 --> 01:22:10.440
with the defeat of
Armenian forces.

01:22:10.440 --> 01:22:12.690
Only the timely humanitarian
intervention

01:22:12.690 --> 01:22:15.590
of the Bolsheviks prevented
the complete destruction

01:22:15.590 --> 01:22:17.680
of the Armenian people.

01:22:17.680 --> 01:22:20.380
This version also served the
interests of the communist party

01:22:20.380 --> 01:22:23.390
in Armenia by portraying the
Armenian Soviet Socialist

01:22:23.390 --> 01:22:28.590
Republic as the culmination of
Armenian national aspirations,

01:22:28.590 --> 01:22:31.310
thus increasing their
own legitimacy.

01:22:31.310 --> 01:22:34.010
This recounting of
the events of 1918

01:22:34.010 --> 01:22:37.310
and 1920 was an important part
of the soviet grand narrative

01:22:37.310 --> 01:22:40.310
for Armenia, which was
reinforced over the years

01:22:40.310 --> 01:22:43.890
through constant and sustained
propaganda, both in the schools

01:22:43.890 --> 01:22:45.190
and in the public sphere.

01:22:45.190 --> 01:22:48.000
The information that
was publicly available

01:22:48.000 --> 01:22:49.300
about the Independent Republic

01:22:49.300 --> 01:22:52.900
of Armenia was almost
uniformly negative,

01:22:52.900 --> 01:22:56.000
stressing the nationalist
and thus evil character

01:22:56.000 --> 01:22:58.410
of the fledgling state.

01:22:58.410 --> 01:23:02.850
Dashnak became synonymous
with bourgeoisie nationalist,

01:23:02.850 --> 01:23:05.830
and the ultimate
political pejorative,

01:23:05.830 --> 01:23:08.540
as were the terms
Musafatist [assumed spelling]

01:23:08.540 --> 01:23:12.480
in Azerbaijan, Bazmachi [assumed
spelling] in central Asia,

01:23:12.480 --> 01:23:15.870
Menshevik [assumed spelling]
in Georgia, and Banderite

01:23:15.870 --> 01:23:17.170
or Pepurst [assumed
spelling] in Ukraine.

01:23:17.170 --> 01:23:21.900
During Glasnost, however,
this soviet narrative came

01:23:21.900 --> 01:23:25.160
under sustained criticism in
Armenia by both intellectuals

01:23:25.160 --> 01:23:29.010
and the public, as a vigorous
and open debate developed

01:23:29.010 --> 01:23:32.920
on the nature and significance
of the independent republic.

01:23:32.920 --> 01:23:35.590
This was the first
independent Armenian state

01:23:35.590 --> 01:23:37.830
that had been created
since the fall

01:23:37.830 --> 01:23:42.920
of the Mediterranean
Kingdom of Cilicia in 1375.

01:23:42.920 --> 01:23:46.680
The previous lessons transmitted
to the population by Moscow

01:23:46.680 --> 01:23:49.200
through soviet Armenian
historiography were challenged

01:23:49.200 --> 01:23:51.500
by new interpretations.

01:23:51.500 --> 01:23:54.840
These interpretations stress
the important symbolic value

01:23:54.840 --> 01:23:57.680
of the republic as an
independent Armenian state.

01:23:57.680 --> 01:24:02.840
This debate on the independent
republic opened slowly at first,

01:24:02.840 --> 01:24:05.470
as historians and the
public were hesitant

01:24:05.470 --> 01:24:08.600
to openly discuss the
subject of independence.

01:24:08.600 --> 01:24:10.650
There seems to have been
fear among certain circles

01:24:10.650 --> 01:24:13.460
of intellectuals and the
public that discussion

01:24:13.460 --> 01:24:16.050
of the independent republic
would be seen by Moscow

01:24:16.050 --> 01:24:20.030
as a sign of disloyalty
and possible separatism.

01:24:20.030 --> 01:24:22.460
Armenians were already being
accused of these things

01:24:22.460 --> 01:24:25.240
because of their support for
Karabakh, and did not want

01:24:25.240 --> 01:24:28.140
to exacerbate tensions further.

01:24:28.140 --> 01:24:31.090
The only consistent calls
for independence came

01:24:31.090 --> 01:24:33.700
from the Armenian
Self-Determination Union,

01:24:33.700 --> 01:24:36.610
and the supporters of the
dissident Paruyr Hayrikyan.

01:24:36.610 --> 01:24:40.530
At a public rally
on May 28th, 1988,

01:24:40.530 --> 01:24:43.290
which was the 70th
anniversary of the declaration

01:24:43.290 --> 01:24:46.660
of Armenian independence, a
telegram was supposedly sent

01:24:46.660 --> 01:24:49.710
to the Supreme Soviet,
asking for that date

01:24:49.710 --> 01:24:51.610
to be declared Armenian
Independence Day.

01:24:51.610 --> 01:24:54.070
This group had not
yet been able to win

01:24:54.070 --> 01:24:56.950
over the mass public support
for the idea of independence,

01:24:56.950 --> 01:24:58.990
though, and throughout
most of '88,

01:24:58.990 --> 01:25:01.720
the subject of the
independent republic was not

01:25:01.720 --> 01:25:03.500
on the public agenda.

01:25:03.500 --> 01:25:05.930
But as the conflict over
Karabakh intensified,

01:25:05.930 --> 01:25:10.740
and an acceptable political
resolution seemed far-off,

01:25:10.740 --> 01:25:13.270
attitudes began to change.

01:25:13.270 --> 01:25:16.130
This change of opinion about
independence was escalated

01:25:16.130 --> 01:25:19.230
in the aftermath of the
December '88 earthquake,

01:25:19.230 --> 01:25:21.860
and the soviet Armenians --

01:25:21.860 --> 01:25:24.900
excuse me, the soviet
authorities proved incapable

01:25:24.900 --> 01:25:27.650
of alleviating the
suffering of the people.

01:25:27.650 --> 01:25:30.610
Disillusionment with the
authorities was heightened

01:25:30.610 --> 01:25:35.500
by the active participation and
organizational skill of members

01:25:35.500 --> 01:25:38.010
of the Armenian Democratic
Movement.

01:25:38.010 --> 01:25:40.780
Thus, from '89 on, more emphasis

01:25:40.780 --> 01:25:43.240
on the independent
republic became discernible

01:25:43.240 --> 01:25:45.050
in the public sphere.

01:25:45.050 --> 01:25:47.570
This was most noticeable at
the regular mass meetings

01:25:47.570 --> 01:25:49.210
that were held in Yerevan,

01:25:49.210 --> 01:25:52.490
as symbols of the old
republic began to appear.

01:25:52.490 --> 01:25:54.480
The red, blue, and
orange tricolor

01:25:54.480 --> 01:25:57.320
of the independent
republic was in evidence.

01:25:57.320 --> 01:26:01.230
It was considered a great honor
to be the chosen flag-bearer

01:26:01.230 --> 01:26:03.500
by the organizers of
the mass meetings.

01:26:03.500 --> 01:26:07.090
Some of my young friends at the
time made sure they got there

01:26:07.090 --> 01:26:09.880
as early as they could, and
got to know the organizers

01:26:09.880 --> 01:26:13.620
so that they would have an
opportunity to hold the flags.

01:26:13.620 --> 01:26:16.370
And they would be willing to
hold them for hours and hours

01:26:16.370 --> 01:26:18.510
in the blazing sun, and
they thought that that,

01:26:18.510 --> 01:26:21.980
for them, was a great honor.

01:26:21.980 --> 01:26:25.870
Buttons, pins, and other
paraphernalia related

01:26:25.870 --> 01:26:29.010
to the Independent Republic
of Armenia were also produced

01:26:29.010 --> 01:26:32.820
in large numbers by activists,
and distributed at the rallies,

01:26:32.820 --> 01:26:34.780
or sold along the route.

01:26:34.780 --> 01:26:37.890
Public curiosity about this
previously forbidden aspect

01:26:37.890 --> 01:26:41.300
of the Armenian past was
mirrored by an increase

01:26:41.300 --> 01:26:43.520
in scholarly interest.

01:26:43.520 --> 01:26:46.810
One of the more prominent
historians of this new approach,

01:26:46.810 --> 01:26:50.290
who's representative, but
by no means exclusive,

01:26:50.290 --> 01:26:53.220
was Goodrik Sardariyan [assumed
spelling], who wrote extensively

01:26:53.220 --> 01:26:55.030
in the mass media
on the formation

01:26:55.030 --> 01:26:57.230
and development of the republic.

01:26:57.230 --> 01:26:58.530
He developed the idea

01:26:58.530 --> 01:27:00.730
that Armenia's most pressing
problems were the result

01:27:00.730 --> 01:27:04.280
of its lack of statehood, also
noting that Armenians needed

01:27:04.280 --> 01:27:06.900
to be more realistic in their
approach to political life,

01:27:06.900 --> 01:27:10.290
and understand that having
a just cause was not enough

01:27:10.290 --> 01:27:12.230
to ensure victory.

01:27:12.230 --> 01:27:15.100
Sardariyan turned to the history
of the Republic of Armenia

01:27:15.100 --> 01:27:18.800
in an effort to understand
the problems and experiences

01:27:18.800 --> 01:27:20.770
of an independent state.

01:27:20.770 --> 01:27:25.040
He criticized those embraced the
idea of an independent Armenia

01:27:25.040 --> 01:27:27.150
without understanding
the full implications

01:27:27.150 --> 01:27:28.980
of such independence.

01:27:28.980 --> 01:27:31.330
Although he supported
the idea of independence,

01:27:31.330 --> 01:27:35.840
he feared the consequences
of precipitous action.

01:27:35.840 --> 01:27:39.130
He concluded that without a
sober assessment of history

01:27:39.130 --> 01:27:41.010
and Armenia's current situation,

01:27:41.010 --> 01:27:42.960
Armenians would end
the 20th Century

01:27:42.960 --> 01:27:45.660
in the same way that
they started it.

01:27:45.660 --> 01:27:48.940
This stark warning for caution
was echoed in other quarters

01:27:48.940 --> 01:27:52.880
as well, but in the atmosphere
of escalating violence

01:27:52.880 --> 01:27:57.020
against Armenia and Karabakh,
most people concluded

01:27:57.020 --> 01:27:59.440
that independence would
be a better option

01:27:59.440 --> 01:28:03.090
than continued membership
in the Soviet Union.

01:28:03.090 --> 01:28:05.620
In recognition of the
symbolic importance ascribed

01:28:05.620 --> 01:28:09.360
to the Republic of Armenia by
soviet Armenian intellectuals,

01:28:09.360 --> 01:28:12.480
the Academy of Sciences
elected Richard Hovannisian,

01:28:12.480 --> 01:28:15.270
the foremost scholar of
the independent republic,

01:28:15.270 --> 01:28:18.840
to be a member of the
Armenian Academy in 1990.

01:28:18.840 --> 01:28:20.480
This was one of the
very few times

01:28:20.480 --> 01:28:23.210
that a foreign member was
inducted into the academy,

01:28:23.210 --> 01:28:25.550
and was the first time
that a foreign historian

01:28:25.550 --> 01:28:28.200
of the modern period
was allowed in.

01:28:28.200 --> 01:28:30.930
This was a clear signal
that Hovannisian's work

01:28:30.930 --> 01:28:32.230
on the Independent Republic

01:28:32.230 --> 01:28:35.270
of Armenia was considered
indispensible for a fuller

01:28:35.270 --> 01:28:37.910
and more accurate understanding
of modern Armenian history.

01:28:37.910 --> 01:28:42.350
There was much talk among
historians for the need

01:28:42.350 --> 01:28:46.200
to have Hovannisian's work
translated into Armenian as soon

01:28:46.200 --> 01:28:48.910
as possible in order
to prepare the country

01:28:48.910 --> 01:28:52.090
for renewed independence,
renewed statehood.

01:28:52.090 --> 01:28:54.420
The new positive image of
the Independent Republic

01:28:54.420 --> 01:28:57.070
of Armenia presented
Armenian historians --

01:28:57.070 --> 01:29:01.290
presented by Armenian historians
was enthusiastically adopted

01:29:01.290 --> 01:29:05.200
by local nationalists and used
as a symbol of local autonomy

01:29:05.200 --> 01:29:08.690
and sovereignty in their
struggle against Moscow.

01:29:08.690 --> 01:29:09.990
Thus, discussion

01:29:09.990 --> 01:29:12.680
of the independent republic
carried an anti-soviet

01:29:12.680 --> 01:29:15.060
connotation from the outset.

01:29:15.060 --> 01:29:18.370
This was mirrored by many local
Armenian political activists,

01:29:18.370 --> 01:29:22.820
who identified themselves as
dashnaks, although very few

01:29:22.820 --> 01:29:25.850
of them actually knew what the
ARF's political position was,

01:29:25.850 --> 01:29:30.210
or the party's platform, or
the party's goals beyond a free

01:29:30.210 --> 01:29:31.510
and independent Armenia.

01:29:31.510 --> 01:29:34.260
They were nevertheless
calling themselves dashnaks,

01:29:34.260 --> 01:29:37.940
because to them, that
was the symbol for a free

01:29:37.940 --> 01:29:40.100
and independent Armenia.

01:29:40.100 --> 01:29:42.500
In the highly charged
political atmosphere of Armenia,

01:29:42.500 --> 01:29:45.260
for most people, that
meant anti-soviet,

01:29:45.260 --> 01:29:48.060
and being anti-soviet,
in some quarters,

01:29:48.060 --> 01:29:52.520
became increasingly equated
with being pro-Armenian.

01:29:52.520 --> 01:29:55.810
In this new spirit of defiance,
there was a reassessment

01:29:55.810 --> 01:30:00.020
of the foundational
battles of May 1918,

01:30:00.020 --> 01:30:03.830
the battles of Sardarabad,
Bash Abaran and Karakilisa,

01:30:03.830 --> 01:30:08.010
in which Armenians were
able to stop Turkish forces

01:30:08.010 --> 01:30:10.320
from invading the
eastern part of Armenia,

01:30:10.320 --> 01:30:14.290
and finishing the job that
they had started in 1915.

01:30:14.290 --> 01:30:17.650
Soviet historiography had
tended to portray these battles

01:30:17.650 --> 01:30:20.730
as important instances
of self-defense

01:30:20.730 --> 01:30:24.180
which saved the Eastern
Armenians from the same fate.

01:30:24.180 --> 01:30:26.660
They were not viewed, however,
in the context of the founding

01:30:26.660 --> 01:30:28.690
of an independent state.

01:30:28.690 --> 01:30:31.320
Given that Armenian independence
was declared immediately

01:30:31.320 --> 01:30:33.820
after these battles, it
seemed an odd omission,

01:30:33.820 --> 01:30:35.130
but one completely in keeping

01:30:35.130 --> 01:30:37.130
with the ideological
needs of Communist Party.

01:30:37.130 --> 01:30:41.390
As Soviet legitimacy was
called into question,

01:30:41.390 --> 01:30:44.300
these battles took on
an added significance.

01:30:44.300 --> 01:30:47.380
In addition to their importance
as self-defense battles,

01:30:47.380 --> 01:30:50.120
they were also presented
by historians and accepted

01:30:50.120 --> 01:30:53.350
by the public as foundational
events in the process

01:30:53.350 --> 01:30:57.150
of restoring Armenian
independence.

01:30:57.150 --> 01:31:01.520
They ascribed new significance
to all this as the conflict

01:31:01.520 --> 01:31:03.910
of [foreign word]
continued to worsen.

01:31:03.910 --> 01:31:08.420
In Moscow, increasingly -- was
increasingly seen in Armenia

01:31:08.420 --> 01:31:12.120
as unwilling or unable to be an
honest broker between Armenians

01:31:12.120 --> 01:31:14.450
and Azerbaijanis,
the reestablishment

01:31:14.450 --> 01:31:16.810
of an Armenian state was
discussed more frequently.

01:31:16.810 --> 01:31:20.130
It was in the context of
current events that the legacy

01:31:20.130 --> 01:31:22.740
of the republic came
to be viewed.

01:31:22.740 --> 01:31:24.980
Part of this reassessment
consisted of trying

01:31:24.980 --> 01:31:28.840
to draw lessons as to the
root causes of failure.

01:31:28.840 --> 01:31:34.940
In conclusion, the historians
identified three main causes

01:31:34.940 --> 01:31:37.850
for the failure of the
Republic to survive.

01:31:37.850 --> 01:31:41.390
The first cause was
directly related to 1915

01:31:41.390 --> 01:31:44.940
with the destruction of Ottoman
Armenians still occurring

01:31:44.940 --> 01:31:48.140
at the time of the foundation of
the Republic and the territory

01:31:48.140 --> 01:31:52.080
of the fledgling state flooded
with refugees, the establishment

01:31:52.080 --> 01:31:53.470
of independent state was viewed

01:31:53.470 --> 01:31:56.890
as an astonishing
feat in and of itself.

01:31:56.890 --> 01:31:58.570
The second major
factor in the defeat

01:31:58.570 --> 01:32:01.770
of the independent republic
was the attitude and behavior

01:32:01.770 --> 01:32:06.140
of Lenin and the Bolshevik
Party, including Stalin.

01:32:06.140 --> 01:32:08.090
Bolshevik collusion
with Kamala's Turkey

01:32:08.090 --> 01:32:10.490
and the dismemberment
of Armenia only served

01:32:10.490 --> 01:32:14.250
to delegitimize Soviet
rule even further.

01:32:14.250 --> 01:32:17.750
And the third factor, identified
by Armenian historians,

01:32:17.750 --> 01:32:19.120
was the indifference

01:32:19.120 --> 01:32:21.920
and contradictions
among the great powers.

01:32:21.920 --> 01:32:25.220
The promises to end
Ottoman oppression extended

01:32:25.220 --> 01:32:28.430
to the Armenians during the war
led many Armenians to believe

01:32:28.430 --> 01:32:31.500
that their hour of
liberation was at hand.

01:32:31.500 --> 01:32:34.810
These promises went unfulfilled,
however, as the interests

01:32:34.810 --> 01:32:36.960
of the great powers
took precedence

01:32:36.960 --> 01:32:38.800
over any moral obligation
they have --

01:32:38.800 --> 01:32:42.050
may have felt for the
plight of the Armenians.

01:32:42.050 --> 01:32:47.760
So at the end of the Soviet
period Armenians were faced

01:32:47.760 --> 01:32:49.200
with a choice.

01:32:49.200 --> 01:32:53.020
And for most, independence was
not the first choice, right?

01:32:53.020 --> 01:32:54.320
The choice was to try

01:32:54.320 --> 01:32:56.930
to renovate the Soviet
Union to make it work.

01:32:56.930 --> 01:33:00.990
But the way events evolved,
the Armenians had to rethink.

01:33:00.990 --> 01:33:03.380
And so by -- in rethinking
their position,

01:33:03.380 --> 01:33:06.800
they looked to history,
not just to the Republic.

01:33:06.800 --> 01:33:09.360
They also looked to the
ancient and medieval period

01:33:09.360 --> 01:33:12.860
where they were able to show the
continuity of Armenian statehood

01:33:12.860 --> 01:33:16.870
from pre-Christian
era to the present.

01:33:16.870 --> 01:33:19.060
They looked at the
Liberation Movement.

01:33:19.060 --> 01:33:22.490
They looked at our
cultural inheritance,

01:33:22.490 --> 01:33:24.050
our connections with the West.

01:33:24.050 --> 01:33:29.110
And all of those things together
helped delegitimize Soviet rule

01:33:29.110 --> 01:33:32.500
in Armenia and laid the
foundations for independence.

