Venetian-born musician described

02:31:36.790 --> 02:31:38.590
by various Armenians as --

02:31:38.590 --> 02:31:45.300
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

02:31:45.300 --> 02:31:50.410
He was a child prodigy as
first composer and violinist.

02:31:50.410 --> 02:31:54.560
He was prolific as a composer.

02:31:54.560 --> 02:31:59.470
He has two masses, two
requiems, a large number

02:31:59.470 --> 02:32:02.150
of orchestral pieces,
chamber music,

02:32:02.150 --> 02:32:05.040
music for the [inaudible]
instruments,

02:32:05.040 --> 02:32:07.280
some [inaudible]
music, but very little

02:32:07.280 --> 02:32:10.230
of his artwork has
been published at all.

02:32:10.230 --> 02:32:14.210
And, indeed, what he's most
remembered for is the fact

02:32:14.210 --> 02:32:17.040
that he published his
own transcriptions

02:32:17.040 --> 02:32:18.340
of all the [inaudible]

02:32:18.340 --> 02:32:21.810
of the <i>Armenian Divine
Liturgy </i>which he harmonized

02:32:21.810 --> 02:32:26.500
on the basis of the chance
he had heard performed

02:32:26.500 --> 02:32:31.730
by the Venetian [foreign
word] fathers in San Lazarof.

02:32:31.730 --> 02:32:35.640
And that is what he may be
remembered for at the moment,

02:32:35.640 --> 02:32:38.150
although he deserves to be
known very much better both

02:32:38.150 --> 02:32:43.540
in Armenian circles
and in others.

