of the excerpt so that we could
include the magnificent high

02:35:52.920 --> 02:35:54.550
notes with which he ended.

02:35:54.550 --> 02:35:59.890
[Foreign words] was a soloist
in <i>La Scale </i>in Milan and in --

02:35:59.890 --> 02:36:02.840
at the Paris Opera as well.

02:36:02.840 --> 02:36:06.420
And he was singing [foreign
words] with the words

02:36:06.420 --> 02:36:09.820
by Father Ghevont Alishan,
and music by none other

02:36:09.820 --> 02:36:11.240
than Pietro Bianchini,

02:36:11.240 --> 02:36:15.120
the author of the manuscript
I'm going to talk about.

02:36:15.120 --> 02:36:19.070
But one last thing
before I start doing so --

02:36:19.070 --> 02:36:23.990
just to give you a sort
of feel about the circles

02:36:23.990 --> 02:36:26.820
in which Pietro Bianchini
circulated.

02:36:26.820 --> 02:36:29.630
I should like to invite
you to consider three

02:36:29.630 --> 02:36:33.960
of the delicatees [assumed
spelling] of his various works,

02:36:33.960 --> 02:36:36.130
manuscripts, publications.

02:36:36.130 --> 02:36:40.250
They are none other than
King Victor Emmanuel II,

02:36:40.250 --> 02:36:45.680
the King of Italy, for whom
Bianchini composed an orchestral

02:36:45.680 --> 02:36:47.010
piece, [foreign words],

02:36:47.010 --> 02:36:51.050
to celebrate the
annexation of Venice in 1866.

02:36:51.050 --> 02:36:55.060
But the other two were no
less formidable characters

02:36:55.060 --> 02:36:57.980
within the Armenian milieu.

02:36:57.980 --> 02:37:01.880
The middle gentleman
was Abbott General

02:37:01.880 --> 02:37:03.840
of the [inaudible]
Congregation of Venice,

02:37:03.840 --> 02:37:06.320
Archbishop [foreign words].

02:37:06.320 --> 02:37:09.790
A formidable personality
himself,

02:37:09.790 --> 02:37:12.100
and a towering intellectual

02:37:12.100 --> 02:37:15.540
who would deserve a
[inaudible] lecture

02:37:15.540 --> 02:37:18.070
in his own right if
it were possible.

02:37:18.070 --> 02:37:19.730
And the third is nonother

02:37:19.730 --> 02:37:23.280
than the Catholicos
Patriarch Steven Peters,

02:37:23.280 --> 02:37:27.610
Step'anos Petros X Azarean,
who was very distinguished,

02:37:27.610 --> 02:37:29.620
particularly as an
ecclesiastical leader

02:37:29.620 --> 02:37:32.040
and ecclesiastical diplomat.

02:37:32.040 --> 02:37:34.670
And he is the delicatee
[assumed spelling]

02:37:34.670 --> 02:37:40.540
of the beautiful manuscript
that is held by the Library

02:37:40.540 --> 02:37:44.300
of Congress to which I
should now like to turn.

02:37:44.300 --> 02:37:47.270
This is what the
dedication page looks like.

02:37:47.270 --> 02:37:50.380
It is hand-written
by Bianchini himself,

02:37:50.380 --> 02:37:54.210
dedicated to the
patriarch on the occasion

02:37:54.210 --> 02:37:58.910
of the latter's nameday
which was St. Stephen's Day,

02:37:58.910 --> 02:38:03.190
the 26th of December, 1887.

02:38:03.190 --> 02:38:05.930
Bianchini ends the letter

02:38:05.930 --> 02:38:10.980
by seeking the patriarch's
blessing, approaching,

02:38:10.980 --> 02:38:13.750
figuratively, to kiss his hand,

02:38:13.750 --> 02:38:17.640
and declaring himself
a "humble servant."

02:38:17.640 --> 02:38:19.200
Pietro Bianchini.

02:38:19.200 --> 02:38:23.610
And very importantly
Maestro of the Congregation

02:38:23.610 --> 02:38:27.850
of the Mechitarist Fathers
of San Lazzaro in Venice.

02:38:27.850 --> 02:38:30.930
Bianchini spent many
years working

02:38:30.930 --> 02:38:35.610
in San Lazzaro apparently
directing the choir during the

02:38:35.610 --> 02:38:36.960
Divine Liturgy.

02:38:36.960 --> 02:38:40.240
So, in addition to serving as
Director of Music in a number

02:38:40.240 --> 02:38:43.250
of Italian cities,
particularly Northern Italy,

02:38:43.250 --> 02:38:48.440
he performed this very valuable
service to the Armenian Monks.

02:38:48.440 --> 02:38:52.800
Now the ode in question, and
[foreign words], chosen of God,

02:38:52.800 --> 02:38:55.220
is a composition
not of Bianchini's.

02:38:55.220 --> 02:38:58.500
Bianchini merely transcribed
the traditional melody.

02:38:58.500 --> 02:39:02.210
But it is a work that
preoccupied Bianchini

02:39:02.210 --> 02:39:05.190
for several decades in
the course of his career.

02:39:05.190 --> 02:39:10.570
And we have various versions
of it which he worked on.

02:39:10.570 --> 02:39:14.240
The earliest that I know
was published as part

02:39:14.240 --> 02:39:17.900
of a very slim booklet
that is exceedingly rare.

02:39:17.900 --> 02:39:20.950
Not only the Mechitarist
fathers,

02:39:20.950 --> 02:39:24.600
not even the Mechitarist
fathers in Venice in San Lazaro

02:39:24.600 --> 02:39:26.820
or even the Armenian
National Library are

02:39:26.820 --> 02:39:30.550
in possession of a copy.

02:39:30.550 --> 02:39:33.960
And you can see -- that is the
extreme left-hand side corner.

02:39:33.960 --> 02:39:40.190
It consists of two lines,
the melody sung by a soloist,

02:39:40.190 --> 02:39:43.900
and a figured baseline as if it
were a piece of baroque music,

02:39:43.900 --> 02:39:46.600
indicating one line and
with little numbers,

02:39:46.600 --> 02:39:48.900
the chords that should be played

02:39:48.900 --> 02:39:52.120
by the organist or
harmonium player.

02:39:52.120 --> 02:39:57.330
The second version of it
that we encounter is part

02:39:57.330 --> 02:40:00.570
of the entire complete
Divine Liturgy chance.

02:40:00.570 --> 02:40:04.330
These were published
in 1877 in San Lazaro.

02:40:04.330 --> 02:40:09.080
And there, we find the entire
ode complete with an organ

02:40:09.080 --> 02:40:11.460
or harmonium accompaniment.

02:40:11.460 --> 02:40:13.980
But there are also
various manuscripts

02:40:13.980 --> 02:40:16.150
that I have succeeded
in locating

02:40:16.150 --> 02:40:18.020
in the San Lazaro archives

02:40:18.020 --> 02:40:20.360
in which Bianchini
made various copies

02:40:20.360 --> 02:40:24.930
or arrangements particularly
of the choral component

02:40:24.930 --> 02:40:29.470
of the ode typically with
the verbal underlay written

02:40:29.470 --> 02:40:31.920
in Latin script suggesting

02:40:31.920 --> 02:40:36.520
that probably Italian
professional singers would sing

02:40:36.520 --> 02:40:39.950
during the Divine
Liturgies in San Lazaro,

02:40:39.950 --> 02:40:43.410
a fact that I found rather
surprising initially.

02:40:43.410 --> 02:40:46.110
And in one case and that's
the undated manuscript

02:40:46.110 --> 02:40:49.160
that I'm showing you on the
extreme right-hand side,

02:40:49.160 --> 02:40:52.790
he has a string orchestra
accompaniment

02:40:52.790 --> 02:40:56.120
to almost the entire
Divine Liturgy and it seems

02:40:56.120 --> 02:40:57.850
that he had second thoughts.

02:40:57.850 --> 02:41:00.330
You see that he crossed
out the orchestra

02:41:00.330 --> 02:41:05.430
from the first four measures,
deciding that it should be sung

02:41:05.430 --> 02:41:10.580
by solo female voices alone,
one soprano and one alto,

02:41:10.580 --> 02:41:11.880
before the chorus comes

02:41:11.880 --> 02:41:15.570
in on the fifth measure
together with the strings.

02:41:15.570 --> 02:41:19.170
But this is what the version
in our manuscript looks like.

02:41:19.170 --> 02:41:22.930
Again, it is the complete ode
with the first two stanzas

02:41:22.930 --> 02:41:27.700
of the ode to be sung by a
soloist accompanied by harmonium

02:41:27.700 --> 02:41:31.120
or some other suitable
keyboard instrument.

02:41:31.120 --> 02:41:35.830
And the remaining stanzas
are included complete

02:41:35.830 --> 02:41:43.010
to be sung by a choir.

02:41:43.010 --> 02:41:46.470
And after the music, the words

02:41:46.470 --> 02:41:50.140
on their own have also been
beautifully copied out.

02:41:50.140 --> 02:41:54.850
The first two stanzas in a
kind of Armenian Gothic script

02:41:54.850 --> 02:41:57.900
with the word [inaudible]
patriarch highlighted

02:41:57.900 --> 02:42:05.560
by being made larger because
usually the words are [Speaking

02:42:05.560 --> 02:42:09.090
in foreign language], chosen
of God, oh happy, holy priest.

02:42:09.090 --> 02:42:13.780
But the word priest
has been replaced

02:42:13.780 --> 02:42:18.580
by the word patriarch
customizing the ode as it were

02:42:18.580 --> 02:42:22.400
for the person, to the
person of the patriarch.

02:42:22.400 --> 02:42:26.930
And the choral stanzas are
written in a beautiful hand

02:42:26.930 --> 02:42:30.980
in another script which is
characteristic of the period.

02:42:30.980 --> 02:42:34.450
But the crucial thing is that
the entire ode has been included

02:42:34.450 --> 02:42:36.560
and the music for it as well.

02:42:36.560 --> 02:42:40.560
And the verbal text, we can
find in another possession

02:42:40.560 --> 02:42:41.860
of the Library of Congress

02:42:41.860 --> 02:42:45.980
in the beautiful
Constantinopolitan Breviary

02:42:45.980 --> 02:42:49.720
of 1768 where you see
it starts at the bottom

02:42:49.720 --> 02:42:51.580
of the left-hand side page,

02:42:51.580 --> 02:42:57.680
continuing all the way
along the page opposite.

02:42:57.680 --> 02:43:03.810
The verbal text, the poetry
is actually rather beautiful.

02:43:03.810 --> 02:43:08.380
It makes allusions to the
Book of Exodus from the Bible,

02:43:08.380 --> 02:43:12.290
the 28th chapter where
there is a description

02:43:12.290 --> 02:43:17.730
of Moses preparing meticulously
and beautifully woven garments,

02:43:17.730 --> 02:43:20.620
priestly garments for Aaron.

02:43:20.620 --> 02:43:24.640
And the poet, whoever it was who
composed the words of this ode,

02:43:24.640 --> 02:43:29.590
likens the celebrant about
to serve the Divine Liturgy

02:43:29.590 --> 02:43:33.610
to the person of Aaron.

02:43:33.610 --> 02:43:37.320
And in the words of
the poem, it is Christ

02:43:37.320 --> 02:43:41.640
who today makes our celebrant
appear under the same form

02:43:41.640 --> 02:43:47.440
as Aaron and seeks the
intercession of the priest.

02:43:47.440 --> 02:43:51.530
Now, this is full of
polyvalent symbolism

02:43:51.530 --> 02:43:55.850
because if we consider the
liturgical use of the ode,

02:43:55.850 --> 02:43:57.250
we find that in fact, the ode is

02:43:57.250 --> 02:44:00.370
to be sung during the
particularly poignant moment

02:44:00.370 --> 02:44:02.600
in the beginning of
the Divine Liturgy.

02:44:02.600 --> 02:44:07.450
During those moments when the
celebrant, being the bishop

02:44:07.450 --> 02:44:11.340
or of higher rank, is
to fall on his knees

02:44:11.340 --> 02:44:15.640
and with overflowing tears --
these are not my words but those

02:44:15.640 --> 02:44:20.470
of the rubric, the instructions
in the missal and I'm quoting

02:44:20.470 --> 02:44:24.010
from another beautiful
Library of Congress manuscript,

02:44:24.010 --> 02:44:28.210
a missal from the year
1722 where you can see

02:44:28.210 --> 02:44:30.010
on the left-hand
side the situation.

02:44:30.010 --> 02:44:31.800
The celebrant is kneeling.

02:44:31.800 --> 02:44:36.700
The proto deacon, the chief
deacon has taken his miter away

02:44:36.700 --> 02:44:41.320
and the celebrant is to recite
the very beautiful prayer

02:44:41.320 --> 02:44:44.670
by Saint Gregory of
Narek in two parts,

02:44:44.670 --> 02:44:48.050
addressed to the Holy
Spirit which he has

02:44:48.050 --> 02:44:50.910
to do quietly and
inexpressively.

02:44:50.910 --> 02:44:52.990
The Armenian word is [Speaking

02:44:52.990 --> 02:44:54.290
in foreign language]
corresponding

02:44:54.290 --> 02:44:57.370
to the Greek [Speaking in
foreign language] which in turn,

02:44:57.370 --> 02:45:00.890
harks back to the Book
of Romans, chapter eight

02:45:00.890 --> 02:45:05.460
where Saint Paul refers to our
own inability to pray properly

02:45:05.460 --> 02:45:10.310
but that fortunately, the
Holy Spirit utters these

02:45:10.310 --> 02:45:12.410
inexpressible groans by way

02:45:12.410 --> 02:45:15.320
of interceding on
our behalf to God.

02:45:15.320 --> 02:45:18.260
So you can see there are all
sorts of layers of associations.

02:45:18.260 --> 02:45:20.550
The celebrant kneels.

02:45:20.550 --> 02:45:24.900
He recites quietly this
prayer during which time,

02:45:24.900 --> 02:45:27.640
someone has to sing this ode.

02:45:27.640 --> 02:45:30.080
And if you were in the
position of singing the ode,

02:45:30.080 --> 02:45:34.610
as I have been, you can never
predict how long this is going

02:45:34.610 --> 02:45:35.910
to take.

02:45:35.910 --> 02:45:39.050
How many stanzas of the ode you
will require because the rubric

02:45:39.050 --> 02:45:42.200
in the middle of the prayer
to the Holy Spirit says

02:45:42.200 --> 02:45:45.680
that the celebrant has to repeat
the first part of the prayer

02:45:45.680 --> 02:45:52.450
as many times as it takes
until such time as confidence

02:45:52.450 --> 02:45:54.230
in the upward contemplation

02:45:54.230 --> 02:45:58.170
of light be wonderfully
revealed to the celebrant.

02:45:58.170 --> 02:46:00.180
As you might imagine,
one cannot predict

02:46:00.180 --> 02:46:05.240
in advance how long it will
take for such confidence

02:46:05.240 --> 02:46:08.390
in the upward contemplation
of light and the revelation

02:46:08.390 --> 02:46:11.590
of this light will take.

02:46:11.590 --> 02:46:16.380
And so, Bianchini was very wise
in providing the entire text

02:46:16.380 --> 02:46:19.710
with music just in case.

02:46:19.710 --> 02:46:21.490
It is a very beautiful
moment, the celebrant

02:46:21.490 --> 02:46:25.350
and the singer both kneel
and usually these days,

02:46:25.350 --> 02:46:29.670
unlike this image where the
celebrant is holding the missal

02:46:29.670 --> 02:46:32.330
himself from which
to read the prayer.

02:46:32.330 --> 02:46:38.840
Two deacons also kneel holding
the missal on either side.

02:46:38.840 --> 02:46:42.450
This is another illustration
from Matenadaran missal

02:46:42.450 --> 02:46:45.880
of about the same period.

02:46:45.880 --> 02:46:50.770
You can see the deacons behind.

02:46:50.770 --> 02:46:54.760
One is holding the miter and
the celebrant is kneeling

02:46:54.760 --> 02:46:56.820
and saying the prayer.

02:46:56.820 --> 02:47:00.650
Rather more recently than the
18th Century, last October,

02:47:00.650 --> 02:47:03.400
I had the enormous pleasure
of bringing this melody back

02:47:03.400 --> 02:47:09.240
to life by singing this
Bianchini version of the ode

02:47:09.240 --> 02:47:11.610
in the Church of the Holy
Sepulchre in Jerusalem.

02:47:11.610 --> 02:47:15.800
I was not, of course, singing
from the beautiful Library

02:47:15.800 --> 02:47:18.990
of Congress manuscript
itself but rather

02:47:18.990 --> 02:47:20.290
from an electronic scan

02:47:20.290 --> 02:47:25.100
of it very kindly made
available to me by Levon.

02:47:26.250 --> 02:47:30.560
Now, you might like to
ask how old this ode is.

02:47:30.560 --> 02:47:33.490
Since when did it
come into existence?

02:47:33.490 --> 02:47:35.760
It is a question that I
have not been able to answer

02:47:35.760 --> 02:47:41.530
with certainty but I
have tried my best.

02:47:41.530 --> 02:47:45.180
We have the very great benefit
that there is a fine catalog

02:47:45.180 --> 02:47:50.030
by the later Father [Inaudible],
the former abbot of San Lazaro,

02:47:50.030 --> 02:47:53.550
where you can look up
all the odes that are

02:47:53.550 --> 02:47:56.850
in all the manuscripts
in San Lazaro,

02:47:56.850 --> 02:47:59.670
looking up their first lines.

02:47:59.670 --> 02:48:02.020
And there are over
60 manuscripts

02:48:02.020 --> 02:48:05.720
that could include this ode
which include odes and litanies.

02:48:05.720 --> 02:48:11.370
And only a single one out of
those 66 manuscripts, I think,

02:48:11.370 --> 02:48:13.620
if I'm right, includes the ode.

02:48:13.620 --> 02:48:16.590
And it is a rather
recent manuscript

02:48:16.590 --> 02:48:18.550
as Armenian manuscripts go,

02:48:18.550 --> 02:48:22.260
being copied out
in the year 1663.

02:48:22.260 --> 02:48:26.160
As it happens, in the Armenian
Church of the Holy Cross

02:48:26.160 --> 02:48:28.470
in Venice, a stone's throw

02:48:28.470 --> 02:48:31.800
from Saint Mark's
Basilica, as it happens.

02:48:31.800 --> 02:48:35.110
Moreover, we read that the
manuscript was discovered

02:48:35.110 --> 02:48:37.360
in the 19th Century
by none other

02:48:37.360 --> 02:48:41.550
than the poet monk Father Lewond
Alisan whose [Inaudible] we

02:48:41.550 --> 02:48:44.360
heard a moment ago
to Bianchini's music.

02:48:44.360 --> 02:48:46.620
This is what the
manuscript looks like.

02:48:46.620 --> 02:48:48.640
But alas, although other items

02:48:48.640 --> 02:48:51.490
in the manuscript have
musical signs on them,

02:48:51.490 --> 02:48:54.120
this particular ode, the
ode that interests us,

02:48:54.120 --> 02:48:56.570
does not bear musical signs.

02:48:56.570 --> 02:49:00.290
But if we look at the
[Inaudible] Monastery in Vienna,

02:49:00.290 --> 02:49:03.320
there is a manuscript
from about the same period

02:49:03.320 --> 02:49:05.890
but it cannot be clearly dated

02:49:05.890 --> 02:49:07.980
as it does not have
a [inaudible]

02:49:07.980 --> 02:49:11.810
which does bear musical
signs known as neumes.

02:49:11.810 --> 02:49:15.110
Now, that does not necessarily
help us quite as much

02:49:15.110 --> 02:49:17.910
as one might hope because
we are sadly unable

02:49:17.910 --> 02:49:20.680
to decipher the medieval neumes.

02:49:20.680 --> 02:49:23.840
But we can tell various
things by looking

02:49:23.840 --> 02:49:27.010
at the notation over the words.

02:49:27.010 --> 02:49:29.120
We can see that the
melody, whatever it was,

02:49:29.120 --> 02:49:32.170
must have been fairly
simple because the density

02:49:32.170 --> 02:49:34.580
of the neumes is not
particularly high.

02:49:34.580 --> 02:49:37.870
And we mostly see
rather simple signs.

02:49:37.870 --> 02:49:40.480
But we can do a bit
better than that.

02:49:40.480 --> 02:49:43.910
We are extremely fortunate
in that a very great genius

02:49:43.910 --> 02:49:46.790
and probably the greatest
Armenian musicologist

02:49:46.790 --> 02:49:48.500
of modern times,

02:49:48.500 --> 02:49:52.510
the Constantinopolitan
Church musician Elia Tntesean

02:49:52.510 --> 02:49:58.240
who belonged more or less to the
same generation as Bianchini,

02:49:58.240 --> 02:50:00.220
carried out a lot of astute

02:50:00.220 --> 02:50:06.260
and meticulous detective
work enabling him not perhaps

02:50:06.260 --> 02:50:09.080
to decipher the meaning
of the neumes

02:50:09.080 --> 02:50:11.220
but to develop a conjecture,

02:50:11.220 --> 02:50:15.840
quite a convincing conjecture
although it is not quite 100%

02:50:15.840 --> 02:50:20.420
water tight, according
to which we can tell

02:50:20.420 --> 02:50:23.930
with reasonable certainty
the metrical durations

02:50:23.930 --> 02:50:28.910
of particular syllables
bearing some neumes

02:50:28.910 --> 02:50:31.610
or bearing no neumes at all.

02:50:31.610 --> 02:50:36.820
And if we apply his conjecture
to this manuscript of this ode,

02:50:36.820 --> 02:50:44.510
we find that there is, indeed, a
very exciting rhythm as follows.

02:50:44.510 --> 02:51:05.040
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

02:51:05.040 --> 02:51:08.170
It continues like this but
then in the middle of the ode,

02:51:08.170 --> 02:51:11.510
things get more exciting and the
rhythm changes and it becomes --

02:51:11.510 --> 02:51:19.070
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

02:51:19.070 --> 02:51:20.370
And then it returns

02:51:20.370 --> 02:51:23.430
to the regular five-four
sort of rhythm.

02:51:23.430 --> 02:51:27.080
There is a sort of dance-like
lilt to it, isn't there?

02:51:27.080 --> 02:51:31.790
And I think that this is,
indeed, the sort of meter

02:51:31.790 --> 02:51:35.100
that would have -- that the
ode would have been sung to.

02:51:35.100 --> 02:51:38.880
Now, none of the melodies that
are available to us at present

02:51:38.880 --> 02:51:43.750
from various traditions
correspond to the neumes

02:51:43.750 --> 02:51:48.220
because they are far more slower
and ornate melodies with a lot

02:51:48.220 --> 02:51:51.000
of notes being sung
to a single syllable.

02:51:51.000 --> 02:51:54.990
But it is interesting to go back

02:51:54.990 --> 02:51:59.570
and see what perhaps
this ode may have sounded

02:51:59.570 --> 02:52:03.570
like although alas, we are not
able to reconstruct the melody,

02:52:03.570 --> 02:52:07.560
only the meter and the rhythm
which we are able to do,

02:52:07.560 --> 02:52:11.950
thanks to the pioneering
work of Elia Tntesean.

02:52:13.460 --> 02:52:19.300
Now, let us turn to the melody

02:52:19.300 --> 02:52:22.930
that Bianchini was
able to transcribe.

02:52:22.930 --> 02:52:27.160
Before I do so, however, I
should like briefly to refer

02:52:27.160 --> 02:52:31.690
to a little pink slip of paper
that I found bound in the one

02:52:31.690 --> 02:52:33.940
of the Bianchini
manuscripts found

02:52:33.940 --> 02:52:36.490
in the archives of San Lazaro.

02:52:36.490 --> 02:52:39.390
On this occasion, as
on other occasions,

02:52:39.390 --> 02:52:43.290
Bianchini was painstakingly
leaving instructions

02:52:43.290 --> 02:52:46.290
to his singers, probably
Italian singers,

02:52:46.290 --> 02:52:51.170
as to how Armenian sacred
music ought to be performed.

02:52:51.170 --> 02:52:53.640
And his instructions
and by saying

02:52:53.640 --> 02:52:59.000
that if these chants are
performed as they should,

02:52:59.000 --> 02:53:03.870
then the result renders
them sublime and celestial

02:53:03.870 --> 02:53:06.950
and that one and the
same time, most pleasing

02:53:06.950 --> 02:53:10.550
to our hearts and to our ears.

02:53:10.550 --> 02:53:13.960
It is daunting having
sighted these words

02:53:13.960 --> 02:53:16.640
to make a feeble attempt to
sing a bit of the melody to you.

02:53:16.640 --> 02:53:21.620
It is not my singing that
will be sublime and celestial

02:53:21.620 --> 02:53:26.200
but I do hope that my singing
notwithstanding the melody may

02:53:26.200 --> 02:53:29.480
perhaps correspond to
such a description.

02:53:29.480 --> 02:53:31.620
There would be only
a little sound bite

02:53:31.620 --> 02:53:35.510
so that we do not miss the
reception this evening.

02:53:35.510 --> 02:56:14.120
[ Music ]

02:56:14.120 --> 02:56:16.620
And it continues in this vein.

02:56:16.620 --> 02:56:18.510
Time is --

02:56:18.510 --> 02:56:26.500
[ Applause ]

02:56:26.500 --> 02:56:28.420
I thank you for the
applause which naturally,

02:56:28.420 --> 02:56:31.630
I take as being directed
to three people,

02:56:31.630 --> 02:56:35.710
Bianchini who transcribed it,
whoever composed the melody,

02:56:35.710 --> 02:56:39.780
and of course, the poet
who composed the words.

02:56:39.780 --> 02:56:41.660
But it is a privilege to serve

02:56:41.660 --> 02:56:47.420
as their advocate in
my very small way.

02:56:47.420 --> 02:56:53.350
Now, a question rose in my mind
as I was preparing this lecture.

02:56:53.350 --> 02:56:56.750
It was very clear to me from
all the materials that I saw

02:56:56.750 --> 02:57:00.190
and from the meticulous
and painstaking nature

02:57:00.190 --> 02:57:03.130
of the transcription of
this beautiful manuscript

02:57:03.130 --> 02:57:07.070
and the general care that had
been taken in its production

02:57:07.070 --> 02:57:10.480
on the part of Bianchini
and it is abundantly obvious

02:57:10.480 --> 02:57:14.440
that this man was enamored
of Armenian sacred music

02:57:14.440 --> 02:57:19.110
into which he had immersed
himself in a very, very big way.

02:57:19.110 --> 02:57:20.590
And although he had
a very active

02:57:20.590 --> 02:57:24.670
and distinguished career writing
a lot of pieces in the tradition

02:57:24.670 --> 02:57:28.240
of his day -- non-Armenian
pieces, of course --

02:57:28.240 --> 02:57:31.520
I wondered if there
could be some means

02:57:31.520 --> 02:57:34.570
of finding any possible
connections might he have been

02:57:34.570 --> 02:57:39.900
somehow influenced by his
immersion into the sound world

02:57:39.900 --> 02:57:43.510
of these ancient Armenian
chants and their modality

02:57:43.510 --> 02:57:47.720
in his compositions
in a western style.

02:57:47.720 --> 02:57:51.500
Alas, most of his pieces are
unpublished and one needs

02:57:51.500 --> 02:57:53.610
to travel to all sorts
of places in Italy

02:57:53.610 --> 02:57:56.610
and gradually uncover them,
something that God willing,

02:57:56.610 --> 02:57:59.550
I should very much like
to do in future years.

02:57:59.550 --> 02:58:04.180
But upon conducting the
Bianchini Symphonia of 1863

02:58:04.180 --> 02:58:06.580
and remember, it
was composed a year

02:58:06.580 --> 02:58:12.350
after Bianchini published this
ode in a little booklet in 1862,

02:58:12.350 --> 02:58:14.150
only a year previously.

02:58:14.150 --> 02:58:18.620
After having conducted the
piece, I looked at the score

02:58:18.620 --> 02:58:23.770
and then I was struck
by what one might refer

02:58:23.770 --> 02:58:26.650
to as a little oddity.

02:58:26.650 --> 02:58:29.260
The melody that I
sang of the ode,

02:58:29.260 --> 02:58:31.510
it has a very characteristic
motif.

02:58:31.510 --> 02:58:41.640
[ Music ]

02:58:41.640 --> 02:58:46.310
And this occurs twice
in the first stanza

02:58:46.310 --> 02:58:50.090
and another two occasions
in the second stanza.

02:58:50.090 --> 02:58:52.440
And it tends to linger in
the mind, at least it stayed

02:58:52.440 --> 02:58:54.510
in my mind when I first
looked at the ode.

02:58:54.510 --> 02:59:01.040
[ Music ]

02:59:01.040 --> 02:59:04.350
And yet, you will recall that
the symphony that we heard,

02:59:04.350 --> 02:59:07.510
the Symphonia with which
we started has the theme --

02:59:07.510 --> 02:59:13.060
[ Music ]

02:59:13.060 --> 02:59:15.920
Now, if we forget about
the rhythm and just look

02:59:15.920 --> 02:59:17.720
at the notes and the skeleton --

02:59:17.720 --> 02:59:24.490
[ Music ]

02:59:24.490 --> 02:59:29.470
-- it is almost identical to
that of the motif in the ode.

02:59:29.470 --> 02:59:33.420
This is pure speculation on
my part, ladies and gentlemen.

02:59:33.420 --> 02:59:37.460
It might be just the
fancy but I like to think

02:59:37.460 --> 02:59:40.100
that subconsciously possibly,

02:59:40.100 --> 02:59:44.120
this motif from [Inaudible]
may have lingered

02:59:44.120 --> 02:59:47.330
in Bianchini's mind
and somehow re-emerged

02:59:47.330 --> 02:59:50.050
as the theme of this Symphonia.

02:59:50.050 --> 02:59:53.490
I don't know if this
is indeed the case.

02:59:53.490 --> 02:59:56.390
We're not in a position
to ask the master

02:59:56.390 --> 03:00:00.050
but it's an intriguing
thought nonetheless.

03:00:00.050 --> 03:00:03.960
I should like to end by
saying that this was an age

03:00:03.960 --> 03:00:10.680
of cultural titans, people like
Lewond Alisan, [Inaudible],

03:00:14.070 --> 03:00:17.330
many others, Elia Tntesean
-- Bianchini himself,

03:00:17.330 --> 03:00:19.990
I would also put
in that category.

03:00:19.990 --> 03:00:24.800
And it was an exciting era not
only because of an awakening

03:00:24.800 --> 03:00:27.830
on the part of the Armenians
but because of the very,

03:00:27.830 --> 03:00:31.380
very beautiful fruits
that emerged as the result

03:00:31.380 --> 03:00:34.970
of the interaction between
Armenian and European cultures.

03:00:34.970 --> 03:00:38.590
And this happened
not only in music.

03:00:38.590 --> 03:00:42.450
It happened in terms of
spirituality and theology.

03:00:42.450 --> 03:00:45.080
It happened in literature
particularly

03:00:45.080 --> 03:00:47.570
in poetry as we all know.

03:00:47.570 --> 03:00:51.720
And this manuscript
documents precisely that.

03:00:51.720 --> 03:00:54.870
It exemplifies and embodies
one of those fruits,

03:00:54.870 --> 03:00:57.770
a Venetian Italian
music transcribing

03:00:57.770 --> 03:00:59.520
into western notation

03:00:59.520 --> 03:01:04.000
and harmonizing an
ancient Armenian ode.

03:01:04.000 --> 03:01:07.920
Had he not transcribed it, we
would probably have lost it

03:01:07.920 --> 03:01:10.460
because this melody is not known

03:01:10.460 --> 03:01:15.250
to the San Lazaro
monks at present.

03:01:15.250 --> 03:01:19.650
And this manuscript is like
a diamond that sheds light

03:01:19.650 --> 03:01:22.370
in all sorts of direction
suggesting avenues

03:01:22.370 --> 03:01:24.110
for future research.

03:01:24.110 --> 03:01:27.750
And I feel so very
fortunate and blessed

03:01:27.750 --> 03:01:31.940
that this manuscript has
been preserved and these kept

03:01:31.940 --> 03:01:35.810
at the Library of Congress
for our own generation

03:01:35.810 --> 03:01:40.530
and future generations
to study and to enjoy.

03:01:40.530 --> 03:01:42.830
And moreover, it is here

03:01:42.830 --> 03:01:46.340
where it is really disseminated
electronically to anyone

03:01:46.340 --> 03:01:49.960
who may care to have a look at
it which is something that is

03:01:49.960 --> 03:01:52.980
of very great value and which
the Library of Congress shares

03:01:52.980 --> 03:01:55.400
with the National
Library of Armenia.

03:01:55.400 --> 03:01:59.710
And I feel above all, a
tremendous and profound debt

03:01:59.710 --> 03:02:02.430
of gratitude to Dr.
Levon Avdoyan,

03:02:02.430 --> 03:02:06.510
thanks to whose excellent
nose for such things

03:02:06.510 --> 03:02:10.380
and unerring instinct
and his untiring efforts,

03:02:10.380 --> 03:02:12.770
this manuscript has
been acquired

03:02:12.770 --> 03:02:15.260
by the Library of Congress.

03:02:15.260 --> 03:02:19.200
So please accept my
gratitude for this as well

03:02:19.200 --> 03:02:25.160
as many other things of which
today's unique conference is

03:02:25.160 --> 03:02:26.460
but one.

03:02:26.460 --> 03:02:30.450
In thanking Levon, I should
also like to thank a number

03:02:30.450 --> 03:02:34.220
of other individuals
and these institutions

03:02:34.220 --> 03:02:38.000
without whose generosity
and kindness,

03:02:38.000 --> 03:02:41.350
this research would
not have been possible.

03:02:41.350 --> 03:02:42.650
Thank you very much indeed

03:02:42.650 --> 03:02:44.510
for your attention,
ladies and gentlemen.

03:02:44.510 --> 03:02:53.080
[ Applause ]

03:02:53.080 --> 03:02:58.860
&gt;&gt; Levon Avdoyan: Alas, this day
has actually flown by for me.

03:02:58.860 --> 03:03:02.150
It's been a combination of
several months of planning.

03:03:02.150 --> 03:03:06.940
I would truly want to thank all
of my speakers, our speakers,

03:03:06.940 --> 03:03:11.260
some of whom have come
from long distances abroad

03:03:11.260 --> 03:03:13.740
and are going to leave sadly.

03:03:13.740 --> 03:03:18.800
It is -- people who know me,

03:03:18.800 --> 03:03:21.840
I usually just say thank
you if I'm not pleased.

03:03:21.840 --> 03:03:25.740
What I am going to say is
true in every single case

03:03:25.740 --> 03:03:27.260
which is each and every one

03:03:27.260 --> 03:03:30.470
of these papers has
exceeded my expectations

03:03:30.470 --> 03:03:33.660
of what I hoped would happen.

03:03:33.660 --> 03:03:37.040
And I hope those of you who have
lasted all day, will go away

03:03:37.040 --> 03:03:39.650
with what I wanted you to feel

03:03:39.650 --> 03:03:44.130
which is Armenian
history is extremely more

03:03:44.130 --> 03:03:47.470
than just a few isolated facts.

03:03:47.470 --> 03:03:48.850
So thank you for attending.

03:03:48.850 --> 03:03:51.280
Thank you for my
wonderful speakers.

03:03:51.280 --> 03:03:54.910
And I hope you will all attend
the Smithsonian Folk Life

03:03:54.910 --> 03:03:56.750
Festival in the next two weeks

03:03:56.750 --> 03:03:59.640
and enjoy Armenian culture
on a different plane.

03:03:59.640 --> 03:04:01.440
Thank you.

03:04:01.440 --> 03:04:22.090
